<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Buddy swung,'' singer <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said Friday before opening the <ORGANIZATION> JVC </ORGANIZATION> Jazz Festival concert celebrating the music of the late drummer and band leader <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>. `` He drummed the impossible drum,'' <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recording </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, said in giving a citation of merit to <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>'s daughter <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, who produced the concert. The evening at <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> was a mixture of the classy and the homey. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Torme </PERSON> sang impeccably and with warmth. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellson </PERSON> played a couple of exciting and varied drum solos. There were film clips of <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> in the late 1930s and early 1940s with the <PERSON> Artie </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> bands. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> sang `` There Will Never Be Another You'' and `` Honeysuckle Rose'' in front of the Buddy Rich Big Band. <PERSON> Torme </PERSON> included `` Here's That Rainy Day,'' which he said was <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>'s favorite from a 1978 album they made, `` Together Again for the First Time. <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> sang a song praising her father while slides from the family scrapbook were shown. The last number was the lengthy `` Two in One Suite,'' with <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>'s drumming recorded in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> in 1968 and the band playing. <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dominick </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, souding very good, sang new, sometimes treacly lyrics in praise of <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>. Also appearing were saxophonist <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Getz </PERSON>, who played <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' `` Yours and Mine,'' which he and <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> once heard together at the <ORGANIZATION> Village </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION>, and singers <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendricks </PERSON> and Company and <PERSON> Marlena </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, who died in 1987 at age 69, was a self-taught drummer credited with `` the fastest hands in the world.'' His career spanned vaudeville, the Big Band era and decades on the road.
