<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Beilenson </PERSON>, who helped found the Screen Actors Guild and other <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> unions in the 1930s as well as serving such clients as then-actor <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, died Monday of a stroke. He was 89. <PERSON> Beilenson </PERSON> helped to found or organize the original <ORGANIZATION> Screen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, the Screen Actors Guild, the <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION>. The writers guild later became the Writers Guild of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Beilenson </PERSON> was a staff lawyer with SAG from its start in 1933, helped negotiate SAG's first contract with film producers in 1937, and stayed on as counsel until 1949. His show business clients ranged from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> to <PERSON> Groucho </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>. After retiring from SAG he served as legal counsel to <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and wrote three books, `` The Treaty Trap,'' `` Power Through Subversion'' and `` Survival and Peace in the Nuclear Age.''
