<BYLINE>Bill Roberts</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, 63, a veteran political manager who engineered President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s early campaign triumphs and a major figure in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Republican politics for more than three decades, died Thursday. Among hundreds of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> campaigns managed by <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, either independently or with longtime colleague <PERSON> Stu </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, were <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s successful campaigns for governor in 1966 and 1970 and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>'s gubernatorial campaign in 1982. The most recent statewide campaign managed by <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was the successful drive in 1986 to remove Chief Justice Rose Bird and Justices <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Grodin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynoso </PERSON> from the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
