<HEAD>Campaign Under Way to Save Old Architecture in Brazil</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA GENASCI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALVADOR, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 International celebrities, including music star <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, have joined in a campaign to save the world's largest example of Portuguese colonial architecture in downtown <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, one of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>'s oldest cities. The 91-acre district is now a slum. It is called <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> word for `` pillory,'' stemming from <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s former slave trade. <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>'s largely abandoned facades line the narrow streets of the city that also was <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s first capital and sometimes is known to outsiders as <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION>, the name of the coastal city's state. In addition to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, other international celebrities involved in the campaign include the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> crooner <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Iglesias </PERSON> and <PERSON> Akio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morito </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Of the district's 978 buildings, some dating as far back as the 1500s, 300 are close to collapse, 48 are in ruins, and about 10 slide down hillsides every year in seasonal rainstorms, according to <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON>, coordinator of the save-Pelourinho campaign <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>'s spacious mansions housed the elite when <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> was, until 1763, the capital of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s vast South American Colony. Today it is a Skid Row, home to prostitutes, drug dealers and muggers. `` <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION> must be the world's largest Baroque slum,'' said the <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION> state secretary for culture, <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Gil </PERSON>, who also is a popular singer and composer. `` There are people in this city who have n't dared venture into <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION> for the past 20 years.'' But for the first time authorities, encouraged by private business, have launched a massive campaign to clean up the winding streets and half-collapsed mansions, which in 1987 were designated by <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> as part of mankind's `` cultural heritage.'' The buildings are protected from demolition by a local decree. `` If we do n't do something now, the whole beautiful area will be completely irrecoverable in 10 years,'' said Ms. <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON>, an engineer. But conversely, it was after the <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> designation that the colonial buildings, arcades, courtyards and cobblestone streets began fell into greater disarray. `` Landlords refused to invest in their properties, which were inhabited by tenants who could pay almost no rent,'' <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> said. `` And they were n't allowed to tear down their buildings. So the strategy was to let the buildings literally fall down _ with tenants inside them.'' So far, the so-called Historical Park of <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>, operating with 150 functionaries borrowed from various municipal government offices, has raised the equivalent of about $ 7 million in government grants and loans, Ms. <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> said. But organizers hope a media campaign that began in February directed at foreign and domestic business communities will bring in much more. <PERSON> Morita </PERSON>, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Iglesias </PERSON> are featured in 60-second public service announcements asking for donations and encouraging businesses to invest in the area. `` We need Brazilians and others to feel responsible for the area, to understand that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> was born here and want to leave this for their children,'' Ms. <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> said. `` Most of the people who actually live here exist in subhuman conditions and could care less about <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>.'' Black groups have been some of the most active in rallying to save the decaying center, as part of a slow but growing black-consciousness movement in mixed-race <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION> was a major port of entry for slaves from <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> from the 1500s through 1888, when slavery was abolished in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. One of the area's most beautiful buildings, the Rosary of the <ORGANIZATION> Blacks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, was built over a period of 150 years by and for slaves. `` Every stone here was laid with the sweat of blacks,'' said an area resident known only as `` Zoinho.'' `` We have to save this area. It's a monument to our suffering.'' Paulo de <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, 18, lives with his father and four brothers and sisters in two rooms of a massively subdivided old home. He was born in <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION>. `` I would n't leave this place,'' he said. `` This is my home. But if you knocked down our old home and built an apartment building in it's place, we'd be much happier.'' Some residents are worried that increased property values will drive out long-time inhabitants. `` We have to make sure we do n't turn <LOCATION> Pelourinho </LOCATION> into a picture postcard,'' Ms. <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> said. `` The sense of community here is rich and very strong. We need to bring in jobs, schools, health facilities and give people the chance to appreciate the fabulous historicl setting.''
</TEXT>
