TION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deparment </ORGANIZATION> has called <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> a `` convicted terrorist and murderer.'' <PERSON> Montano </PERSON> said <PERSON> Pilliod </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> Thursday night from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> where he had been recalled for consultations Tuesday. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> did not advise the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that it had released <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> until Tuesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said. Mexican officials frequently characterized <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> as a `` political fighter,'' not a criminal, and local news reports usually did not mention <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> conviction in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for murder. <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> was released after serving five years of an eight-year sentence for the 1983 slaying of a Mexican police officer and for entering the country illegally. At the time of that killing, <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> was an escaped convict from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, having fled in 1979 from a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prison after being convicted of weapons and explosives charges in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. After his capture in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pressed without success for his extradition.
