<HEAD>Officials Map Out Pear Thrips Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENNINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials could relax state restrictions on pesticide spraying in an effort to control the pear thrips, an insect blamed for defoliating thousands of acres of maple trees in southern <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. Officials of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forests </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION>, along with experts from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> and entomologists experienced with thrips from other northeastern states, have come up with a research project designed to learn more about the insect's habits, life cycle and impact on maple crops and products. Pear thrips are insects whose feeding habits have damaged and weakened thousands of acres of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> sugarbush, particularly in <LOCATION> Bennington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Windham </LOCATION> counties. The plans that experts have laid to improve the lot of maple trees may involve asking Gov. <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunin </PERSON> to relax her 1986 policy strictly limiting pesticide spraying by state agriculture and transportation officials. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Paine </PERSON>, deputy commissioner of agriculture, has done a control pesticide test spray on a sugarbush in <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION> with state permission to discover the most effective stage to spray in the thrips' life cycle. State forester <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> said recently the committee also wants to check for trends using an earth-orbiting satellite that takes color coded infrared snapshots of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> forest land. The photos, which would cost between $ 10,000 and $ 12,000, could give foresters a better idea of what next year's maple crop will look like since the camera picks up signs of weakness and disease that human eyes can miss. Project members also plan to send out questionnaires to all known <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> sugarmakers, asking them to comment on the extent of thrips damage.
