<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recall the white lies they told each other on their first date, and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON>, remembers her surprise when a friend told her she found the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president sexy. These are a few of the tidbits of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lore that British television viewers will see on July 8, when the first of a three-part series on the life of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is broadcast. The film, shown to journalists Thursday, is filled with varied assessments of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. To Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, the president is `` a revolutionary and he's changed the agenda -LRB- in -RRB- the most sweeping presidency in this country probably since <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>.'' Former budget director <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON> calls <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s economic policies `` the singular greatest episode of sustained economic mismanagement in the 20th-century history of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' But Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says of her husband: `` I think he made people feel good about themselves, good about the country. We now have a strong economy, unemployment is down, interest rates are down. ...'' The film traces <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to his Midwestern boyhood, interviewing friends and schoolmates. Actress Olivia de Havilland recalls <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and the late actor <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> lining up as soldiers so that <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>'s shoulder obscured <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. She says <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> quietly kicked the sand into a mound, `` higher and higher, and finally, when the photographer said, ` All right everybody, let's smile,' the future president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stepped up on the mound and towered over <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>.'' Interviewer <PERSON> Godfrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgson </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> why he spied for the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> on colleagues in the Screen Actors Guild of which he was president. `` They -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- came wanting some advice, some findings on people that I had dealt with, and I got an insight into what was happening to the motion picture business. It did give me a real understanding of the communist menace,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says. Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recalls their first date when, mutually wary, they both said they had `` early morning calls'' so that they could leave early if they did n't like each other. They got home at 2:30 a.m, she says. `` I think by that time both of us knew that neither one us of had an early morning call.'' <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s daughter by his first marriage to actress <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON>, says a friend who saw <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> doing a TV ad dressed as a cowboy exclaimed to her that `` he's so sexy.'' `` I said, my father sexy? You must be kidding. ` No no, he's wonderful. And he is wonderful,'' Miss <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says. During his 50-minute interview, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> describes his wife as `` a helpmeet such as I think every man dreams of having, a relationship that sort of matches your dreams of marriage when you were an adolescent.'' He laughs about claims that she interferes in policy-making. `` She does n't go down and get involved in affairs like disarmament or anything else. She advises me of what she thinks is good for me, and I feel free to confide in her the things that are going on. `` As a matter of fact she's a help just by my knowing that she's up there when I go to meet her at the end of the day.
