<HEAD>Supreme Court Will Take Another Look at Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The constitutionality of the death penalty for juvenile killers again will be on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s agenda next term, a welcome surprise for capital punishment foes. <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingerson </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> to Abolish the Death Penalty, said, `` It's very encouraging. I assumed it would be another couple of years before they took the issue up in another case.'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzschild </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said the court's willingness to restudy the issue `` is very startling.'' But he cautioned against reading too much into the court's announcement `` It's foolish to try and predict what the court will do,'' he said. The justices on Thursday provided a dramatic epilogue to their 1987-88 term by agreeing to consider banning capital punishment for all juvenile murderers when the court returns for the next term on the first Monday in October. Just 24 hours earlier, the court had come close to banning the death penalty for those who commit murders before they are 16. Few expected it would move so quickly to re-examine capital punishment for juvenile killers. But the justices said Thursday they will use cases from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> to reconsider the fate of young killers. The court said it will decide sometime in 1989 whether use of the death penalty for anyone under 18 when the crime was committed violates the Constitution's ban on `` cruel and unusual punishment.'' The court will consider overturning the death sentences of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> death row inmate <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> High </PERSON>, who was 17 when he participated in a 1976 murder, and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> death row inmate <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, who was 16 when he committed a 1985 murder. High was just weeks shy of his 18th birthday when he took part in a gas station robbery in <LOCATION> Taliferro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, in which an 11-year-old boy was shot to death. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> helped rob an <ORGANIZATION> Avondale </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, liquor store. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a store clerk, was fatally stabbed. The National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty said 30 death row inmates nationwide _ out of a total of 2,100 _ were under 18 when they committed their crimes. Of the 100 men and women executed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reinstated capital punishment in 1976, three committed their crimes when they were 17. Since 1948, no one has been executed for a crime committed when he or she was younger than 17. If the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bans the death penalty for those under 18, it would affect most of the 37 states with death penalty laws _ including those that do not specify a minimum age for killers subject to capital punishment and states that specify age limits under 18. On Wednesday, four justices said the death penalty is unconstitutional for those who were younger than 16 when they committed murder. Three justices said the Constitution does not set such age limits for executions. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> provided a fifth vote to throw out the death penalty for a convicted <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> killer who was 15 when he helped kill his former brother-in-law. But <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> stopped just short of calling for abolition of capital punishment for killers under 16. A key vote in next term's cases will be provided by Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who joined the court in February, too late to participate in the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> case. In other action Thursday, the court: _ Agreed to study alleged race discrimination in Alaskan salmon canneries, setting the stage for an important sequel to the court's ruling on Wednesday that makes it easier for workers to prove their bosses are guilty of illegal _ Cleared away the last legal obstacle to a $ 180 million settlement _ with interest now worth some $ 240 million _ between <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans and manufacturers of the herbicide Agent Orange The court let stand rulings dismissing lawsuits by about 300 veterans who challenged the settlement, in which as many as 250,000 others could participate. _ Agreed to decide whether states may ban virtually all lawyer advertisements that feature testimonials or client endorsements The justices will review a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> rule that presumes such ads are false or misleading.
</TEXT>
