<HEAD>Traditional Pork Barrel Bill Comes Up Lean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first fiscal 1989 appropriations bill, a bare-bones energy and water development package, is a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote away from heading to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk. The $ 17.83 billion package worked out by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators cleared the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on a 384-17 roll call Thursday and is expected to win easy <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval next week following the July Fourth recess. The spending bill, the product of a tight-money year, is more noteworthy for what it lacks than what it contains. There is no money to begin construction of the superconducting super collider and, lawmakers say, not a dime to start work on new <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION> water projects. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and staffers say they ca n't recall when even huge budget deficits prevented at least a few new dams or harbor projects from being tossed into the traditional pork barrel bill. The administration is not happy about the lack of construction money for the <ORGANIZATION> SSC </ORGANIZATION>, the multi-billion dollar high-energy physics project that backers say is needed to keep the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> technologically competitive. The White House, however, has not made any veto threats against the energy and water bill as it has against a number of the other 12 spending bills under consideration in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Leaders on both sides the Capitol agreed to give the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> $ 100 million next year to continue preliminary work on the SSC, but they said a decision to build it should be made by the next president. The bill contains money to continue construction work on more than 200 corps and bureau water projects. Although the administration sought six new corps starts, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations committees approved none, taking the position that just one new start would set off a clamor among lawmakers for more. More than two-thirds of the money in the bill _ $ 13.16 billion _ is headed for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, with that agency's nuclear activities for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> accounting for $ 8.1 billion. The non-defense portion of the department's budget would finance a variety of activities, including research into solar and other renewable forms of energy and environmental restoration and safety programs. At the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s insistance, the bill contains $ 3 million to study the `` greenhouse effect,'' the global warming trend that scientists say threatens the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> with climate changes and rising ocean waters. The corps would have $ 11 million less next year than in fiscal 1988 to spend on dams, harbors and other work, including a growing number of shoreline erosion projects. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION>, which operates irrigation and power facilities in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, would get $ 40 million more in fiscal 1989, with more than 40 percent of the money going to three large projects: <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
