<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than one million children in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> officially do not exist because they were born outside state birth control targets, rendering them unable to receive food rations, schooling and job assignments, an official report said. The children, most of whom are under age 10, are commonly referred to as `` black children.'' They are children whose parents did not have their births registered or who were refused registration by local authorities, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. Under <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s one-child policy, officials in each county are responsible for ensuring that each woman has only one child and that the number of births in the county does not exceed the birth target set by the state. Parents are penalized for having more than one child, and officials are penalized if the county goes over the number of births that it is allowed. Officials, however, are financially rewarded if births stay within the target. Some parents did not register births of their second or subsequent children to avoid paying the fine, the paper said. Fines vary from region to region, but are generally $ 270 or more per year for five years, a huge fine by Chinese standards. Some local officials, seeing their bonuses jeapordized by too many births, simply refuse to register new babies, the paper said. In one city in southwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province, local officials refused to register the births of 450 babies because the birth target had already been reached, the report said. Without a residence permit, children are deprived of the rights of a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizen. They do not receive their ration of rice and edible oil, are unable to register for school and will not be able to get a job, join the military or sit for college entrance exams when they grow up, the newspaper said. The problem will become even greater when these children marry and have children of their own, who also will be unable to get residence permits, it said. The situation is most serious in the provinces of <LOCATION> Hebei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shandong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guizhou </LOCATION>. In each of these provinces, `` black children'' number more than 70,000, the report said. State officials have called attention to the problem, saying that the children are innocent victims, the newspaper reported. They said the situation not only hurts the children, it also affects the nation's family planning and population control efforts and creates social problems. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s birth rate hit 2 percent in 1986 and stayed there last year. If the trend continues, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s population of 1.08 billion will double by the year 2030, according to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> for Population Activities. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said that it must keep the birth rate at 1.5 percent if it is to meet its goal of keeping the population under 1.2 billion by the year 2000. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will mark <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s Three Billion Population Day today. In a televised speech for the occasion Chinese Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> said Thursday, `` The country has listed family planning as one of its basic national policies and taken the control of population growth as a strategic task.''
</TEXT>
