<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua Poll,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguans Critical of Sandinistas, Appreciate Soviet Union,
Dislike U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Interamerican, 5th graf, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many Nicaraguans are critical of their leftist government and do n't believe it is democratic, but they think Soviet policies are better than those of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to a private poll. A survey presented Thursday as the first independent poll of Nicaraguan opinion under nine years of <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> rule indicates strong support for President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, 85 percent opposition to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Contra aid, and 68 percent disapproval of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policies in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Asked what they most admire about the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 42 percent of those polled said `` nothing,'' which was the most prevalent answer. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for the past seven years has supported rebels attempting to overthrow the Nicaraguan government. The poll of 1,129 adults in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and research groups in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON>, director of the cosponsoring <ORGANIZATION> Interamerican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said the newly formed, private <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> used accepted scientific polling methods, employing students at <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which he described as the nation's most politically neutral university. The students interviewed 1,129 adults selected at random in five types of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> neighborhoods on June 4-5. <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> did not offer a margin of error for the poll but he said at a news conference that several steps were taken to ensure its integrity and objectivity. But he did note that many educated people who might have given anti-Sandinista views have fled to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with their homes taken over by government officials and military officers. He said about 27 percent of those polled worked for the government, and they were the most supportive of the Sandinistas. Thirty-eight percent of the respondents believed the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>' management of the Nicaraguan economy has been either bad or terrible, while 36 percent described it as fair, and only 22 percent said it was good or excellent. Seventy-four percent of those interviewed said they rated their family's economic situation worse than a year ago, while only 7 percent said it was better. Forty-eight percent said they did not consider the Sandinista government democratic while 40 percent said they did. But there was general support for Sandinista peace efforts and the government's foreign policies A majority supported incorporation of the Contras into the country's political life but most of those interviewed also said they doubted the fighting would end soon. The overall results show the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic blockade of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, along with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the Contra rebels, has alienated even many anti-Sandinista Nicaraguans, <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> received higher positive responses than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> among all income levels on several questions, with higher-income groups being more pro-Soviet and pro-Sandinista than poorer and less-educated Nicaraguans. Future polls _ the research group plans one of people in several <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries later this year _ will attempt to obtain more detail about reaction to Soviet policies, said <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON>. Only 1 percent of the respondents described <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Central American policy as excellent, 7 percent called it good, 17 percent said fair, 40 percent said bad and 28 percent called it terrible. Asked the same question about Soviet policy, 14 percent said it was excellent, 43 percent good, 14 percent fair, 9 percent bad and 4 percent terrible. In evaluating <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s management of the government over the last four years, 42 percent said it was good or excellent, 29 percent fair and 21 percent bad or terrible. <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> said this is a high rating in Latin American terms. He said in a similar poll conducted in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, only 13 percent of respondents gave President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> a good or excellent rating. The poll showed that 28 percent of those interviewed claimed affiliation with the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, 9 percent with liberal or conservative opposition parties and 59 percent said they belonged to no party. <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> said the Nicaraguan government did not interfere with the survey even though laws apparently are still on the books prohibiting independent polling in the country.
