<HEAD>Iranian Silkworm Battery Could Pose New Threat, US Commander Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction of a permanent Silkworm battery by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> near the entrance to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and the feared addition of a more advanced anti-ship missile to the Iranian arsenal may heighten risks to passing tankers, says the commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the region. Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>, the Marine four-star who heads the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters Thursday that completion of the Iranian Silkworm battery at Kuhe-Stak and the possible addition of another Chinese anti-ship missile, the CA-08, could make passage in or out of the gulf more dangerous. But he said that since a daylong naval battle on April 18, in which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> lost two of its four frigates, Iranian forces have steered clear of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships and aircraft. `` They have been very careful not to engage us,'' said <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>. A crack team of electronics experts, sent from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to the gulf, determined several weeks after the clash that, despite reports to the contrary, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had not fired a Silkworm missile at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces during the fray, he said. The false reports were generated by computers hooked up to radars aboard <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships that mistook a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> SM-1 missile fired at an Iranian target for a Silkworm, he said. For about two years, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has had Silkworm missiles at the port of <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> near the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, with the ability to set them up at temporary sites to fire within a matter of hours, said <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>. But the permanent earth and concrete bunker, `` with a 57-mile range missile, will cover the entire <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. It will allow <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to have the missile ready to be fired within five minutes,'' he said. Work on the bunker, first reported in early 1987, was continuing, <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> said in his first briefing with reporters since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> allowed Kuwaiti tankers to fly the Stars and Stripes last summer and began escorting them through the gulf. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> said he was pondering what weapons would be needed to destroy the bunker, but meanwhile was stationing the cruise USS Vincennes, equipped with advanced Aegis radar and air-defense missiles, in position to protect any merchant ship passing throught the straits. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> said the cruiser would be ordered to fire against any <ORGANIZATION> Silkworm </ORGANIZATION> launched, regardless of its intended target. `` The threat is not to our ships'' which have been equipped with defenses against missiles like the Silkworm, `` but to unarmed merchant ships,'' said <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>. `` We are not at war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>. Therefore, before he orders the site bunker destroyed, `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will have to do something to violate international law,'' said the general. Stationing an Aegis cruiser at the Strait of Hormuz may make the decision to fire easier, because if a Silkworm is fired, `` I think it will be a little hard to tell who the target is,'' and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship will try to destroy the attacking missile, he said. And under the rules of engagement in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships and aircraft are under orders to respond agressively to a ship, plane or shore installation they believe is attacking them. `` If they fired a Silkworm at me, I would go get them,'' said <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> said that despite repeated protests from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was continuing to sell advanced arms to the Iranians. He could not specify the exact arms, but said that a ship from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> unloaded weaponry from those countries about once every three months at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>. He said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is believed to have about 20 Silkworms in the southern gulf, probably kept at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, and more such missiles in the northern gulf, and he fears that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has also sold <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> CA-08 missiles. The CA-08 has a more sophisticated guidance system than the Silkworm, which he described as `` primitive,'' but carries a 500-pound warhead compared to the 1,100-pound warhead on the Silkworm.
