<HEAD>Electric Boat Employees Go On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An estimated 10,200 Electric Boat employees went on strike at the company's shipyard here Friday after contract talks with the submarine builder broke down. `` We expect the strike to be strong and well-supported,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, a lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Electric Boat, a division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is one of only two shipyards making nuclear submarines for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, and the only manufacturer of subs capable of carrying the giant Trident ballistic missile. Talks broke down at 11:20 p.m. Thursday after a three-hour last-ditch effort, and the walkout began after midnight. No new talks were planned. Earlier in the day, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> awarded this year's third and final SSN-688 fast-attack submarine contract to Electric Boat. The $ 347.4 million contract will go to EB's main shipyard in here and its other plant, in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingstown </LOCATION>, R.I. The strike does not affect the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> plant. In a letter to employees, shipyard General Manager <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tovar </PERSON> said a strike will not stop submarine construction at the shipyard here. EB arranged to assign 3,000 salaried employees to shipyard jobs in the event of a strike. The two sides stalemated over the union's demand for percentage wage increases and the shipyard's insistence that it could afford no more than cash bonuses to remain competitive in its pursuit of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts. Union members voted earlier Thursday 4,921 to 3,140 to reject the company's latest offer but returned to the bargaining table with 4 -LCB- hours to go before the strike deadline in a last-ditch effort to reach a settlement. Talks began in November to replace a three-year contract that expired Friday. The last strike at the shipyard was in 1975, when the union walked out for five months and the region's economy sagged. In <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, state Labor Commissioner <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Tianti </PERSON> said she would meet on Friday with members of the state's congressional delegation and others to see what could be done to lessen the economic impact of the strike. The union wanted straight hourly wage increases of 5 percent, 4 percent and 4 percent over three years. Electric Boat's `` last, best and final offer,'' presented Monday, calls for bonuses totaling $ 4,250 over three years for a first-class mechanic making $ 12.02 an hour, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sotir </PERSON>, vice president of human resources. The company cited increased competition from the only other submarine shipyard in the country, the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drydock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which pays its workers 60 cents an hour less than <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION>, recently won two contracts for nuclear attack submarines after it underbid Electric Boat. `` If the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wants to get into the cheapest subs around, why do n't they get Yugos?'' said <PERSON> Wes </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamphere </PERSON>, 27, of <PERSON> Griswold </PERSON>, president of the foundry workers local. `` We do n't want to make a million bucks, we're not asking for the world. We just want to keep up.''
