<FIRST>r w PM-BlackBoxes-Commuters     07-01 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Boxes-Commuters,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commuter Planes to Have `Black Box' Recorders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Within three years all but the very smallest commuter aircraft must be equipped with so-called `` black box'' recorders under a new regulation from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Large jetliners already are required to have the recorders which provide information about an aircraft's performance and provide a 30-minute loop tape of conversation in the cockpit. The devices have been critical in finding the cause of many airliner crashes over the years. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> recently cited several commuter accidents in which investigations were hampered because adequate information was not available. But commuter planes of less than 30 seats are not required to have the devices. Under a final <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rule announced Thursday, multi-engine, turbine powered commuter planes carrying more than six passengers and flown by two pilots will be required to have cockpit voice recorders. Slightly larger commuter planes carrying 20 or more passengers will have to be equipped with digital flight data recorders that store such information as air speed, altitude, aircraft pitch and heading. Commuter airlines must have the black box recorders within three years of the effective date of the rule, which is expected to be in 90 days. The cockpit voice recorders must be included in new aircraft and retrofitted into planes already in service. The flight data recorders must be in both new and in-service aircraft with 20 or more seats. There is no retrofit requirement for flight data recorders in the smaller commuter planes of less than 20 seats. `` Although the FDR and <ORGANIZATION> CVR </ORGANIZATION> do not enhance safety by themselves they have proven to be invaluable accident investigation tools and have led to numerous improvements in aviation safety,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>. Last year <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> directed the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to expand its requirements for the `` black box'' recorders to include commuter airlines, which last year carried about 32 million passengers.
</TEXT>
