rking to come up with a way to make sure the current contracts are n't tainted.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> and other committee members attended a closed-door briefing Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> about the case. Two legislators said later they expect numerous indictments. Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>, D-Calif., said officials `` are very, very sure of their case ... It's pretty ironclad. Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, R-Ky., said, `` many, many indictments will be forthcoming I do n't think it will be too long before the first of them will be coming down.'' Rear Adm. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> NIS </LOCATION>, detailed the case for the legislators. He outlined a `` series of interlocking rings of people, kind of like the Olympic flag,'' in which several groups operated independently, according to one source, speaking on condition of anonymity. Earlier, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had rejected <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>'s call for a halt. A freeze could raise weapon costs, force plant layoffs and hurt military readiness, said spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` We would be glad to discuss with the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the question of freezing awards of new contracts while the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is investigating allegations of procurement fraud,'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said. `` But at this point we feel it would be imprudent to apply such a freeze or moratorium.'' The investigation has also spawned its first two pieces of reform legislation. One would overhaul and centralize the purchasing system while the second would try to end to the so-called `` revolving door'' between the private sector and government. Th