<HEAD>AMA Approves AIDS Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with approval of policy to
violate confidentiality in some cases with AIDS patients. Picks up
5th graf, `Dr. Don...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday called on the states to trace the sexual partners of people infected with the AIDS virus and urged prisons to test inmates for exposure to the deadly disease. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> urged doctors, as a last resort, to breach confidentiality rules and warn sexual partners of AIDS patients. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> approved the measures by voice vote along with a package of other AIDS proposals before adjourning its annual policy-making convention. `` I think that contact tracing -LRB- of sexual partners -RRB-, at least in the heterosexual community, has the potential to substantially reduce the proliferation and spread of AIDS,'' said Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON>, executive vice president of the 295,000-member <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s 420-member House of Delegates also approved policies aimed at prohibiting athletes from using steroids, posting health warnings on tanning booths, urging airlines to ban smoking on all domestic flights and evaluating whether health warnings should be required on alcoholic beverages. The delegates passed an amendment that says doctors, as a last resort, have an obligation to depart from their Hippocratic vow of confidentiality to warn sexual partners of persons infected with the AIDS virus. The policy says that doctors should try to persuade patients who are infected with the virus to inform their sexual partners. If the infected person refuses, the doctor should report the person to the local public health department so the officials can warn the sexual partners, under the policy. `` And if that fails, the doctor should tell the people who are at risk directly,'' said Dr. <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS Task Force and the association's assistant executive vice president for medical education and science Dr. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, a delegate from <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, warned that doctors must emphasize the need to protect the identities of AIDS victims. `` I caution us to be very careful to do anything we can to protect confidentiality and to fight any discrimination because it would thwart our efforts to bring this disease under control,'' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> said. The doctors' organization renewed its call for mandatory AIDS-virus testing of all inmates because of the problems of intravenous drug use and homosexuality in prisons, practices that spread the disease. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> adopted a similar prison-testing proposal last year and reapproved it Thursday despite objections from several doctors that it would accomplish little. The doctors approved what <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> said would be `` broad expansions on contact tracing'' of sexual partners to slow the spread of AIDS among heterosexuals. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> said contact tracing had been effective in reducing such other sexually transmitted diseases as syphilis and gonorrhea. The delegates also called on federal and state governments to expand treatment programs for intravenous drug abusers because they pose the most explosive potential for spreading AIDS into the heterosexual population. By 1991, the nation likely will have 270,000 cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, said an <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> progress report issued during the convention. There is no known cure for the disease. Some of the other AIDS policies approved by the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> call for vigorous enforcement of existing anti-discrimination laws to protect AIDS victims against bias in employment, housing and other areas; and urge women to avoid breast feeding if they are infected with the AIDS virus to reduce the chance of giving the disease to their children. Another measure calls for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president to keep public attention focused on the epidemic by creating a new national AIDS commission, identical to the one that just finished its work. Such a panel would be a clearinghouse for AIDS research and `` provide the essential coordination between public and private institutions that are addressing AIDS,'' the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> said. In other action: _ The rapid growth of the commercial tanning industry _ with an estimated 17,500 parlors nationwide _ prompted the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> to declare that tanning booths `` pose potentially significant health risks. Delegates voted to lobby the federal government to require warnings in tanning parlors about the increased risks of skin cancer caused by prolonged exposure to ultraviolet light in tanning booths. _ Delegates continued their longtime war on tobacco use, urging commercial airlines to ban smoking on all domestic flights Federal regulations now prohibit smoking on flights of two hours or less. _ The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> urged state legislatures to prohibit athletes from using steroids to enhance physical prowess Improper use of steroids poses dangerous risks such as impairment of a person's sexual functions
</TEXT>
