<HEAD>Wire Service Guild Ratifies One-Year Contract With UPI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> members at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> voted 95-31 to ratify a one-year contract with <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION>, Guild President <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinle </PERSON> said Thursday's vote `` signals the beginning of an era of peace between the guild and management, and it's one more message to the news industry that we are here for the long haul.'' The vote, which came after 15 months of negotiations, was counted at the guild's office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and announced during the 55th annual convention of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, the parent union of the wire service local. The contract, which runs through July 1, 1989, covers about 700 <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> editorial and other employees in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The agreement was reached May 26 with a new guild negotiating team that took over after another team quit May 9 in a dispute with the guild's executive committee. The old contract expired in April 1987. The new pact replaces work rules imposed by the company when it declared an impasse Nov. 1. Three months after that, operating control of the financially troubled news wire service was transferred from <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> publisher <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON> <PERSON> Rana </PERSON> to <ORGANIZATION> WNW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a media investment company whose chairman is <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> and whose president is <PERSON> Steinle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> said that with a wage increase that took effect Nov. 1 and another scheduled for Nov. 1, 1988, the top minimum pay under the new contract will be $ 670 a week starting in the employee's eighth year of service. Under the old contract, top scale was $ 585 a week, starting in the sixth year. The new pact also improves pensions, restores job security and union dues checkoffs, and continues a health insurance plan put in effect after Nov. 1, <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> said. The guild loses its agency shop provision, under which employees had to pay a fee to the union as a condition of employment, <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> said. `` The executive committee and the negotiating committee were certain this was the best contract available to <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> employees,'' <PERSON> Keane </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, president of the parent <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, called it `` a settlement about which I ca n't say I'm proud, but ... an agreement that was necessary _ necessary for us to survive and equally necessary for <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> to obtain the breathing space needed to regain the viability that has been so sorely in question.'' The company, which lost $ 20 million in 1987, announced March 30 it would seek to reach profitability by eliminating 150 jobs, focusing on business news and embarking on joint electronic ventures.
