<HEAD>Vermont Castings Retires Its Answer to the Model T</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest maker of woodstoves threw a party to mark the demise of its popular Defiant model, the victim of environmental regulations effective today that require new stoves to burn more cleanly. `` The Defiant is a symbol of the end of an era,'' <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Castings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Syme </PERSON> said Thursday, calling the woodstove his company's answer to the Model <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Syme </PERSON> decided to forego the gnashing of teeth and complaints about government regulation Instead, his company designed some new stoves and threw a big party for the company's retiring mainstay. Born in 1975 of the energy crisis, a back-to-the-land ethic and a desire by many to thumb their noses at <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and the big oil companies, the Defiant quickly became a symbol of a lifestyle. More than 130,000 stoves have been sold. <PERSON> Syme </PERSON> was an architect who was trying in the early'70s to integrate woodstoves into some of his designs. `` We looked around and did n't see any good ones,'' he said. He got together with his now deceased brother-in-law <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, a Wall Street investment banker. `` We sensed that there was a consumer need for a good-looking stove -LRB- on which -RRB- you could open the doors and celebrate this thing of bringing flame into your livingroom,'' <PERSON> Syme </PERSON> said. They caught the market's wave just before it swelled and the company became an overnight success. Sales have declined since the heyday, but <PERSON> Syme </PERSON> said the company has settled into a comfortable niche marketing colorful new stoves, often to upscale city dwellers and suburbanites who want a livingroom showpiece. Thanks to the Defiant, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> Castings grew to become the nation's largest woodstove manufacturer and now employs about 400 people, most of them at plants in <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> and nearby <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. Responding to environmental concerns over woodsmoke pollution and the new regulations, the company has introduced two new models designed to cut down on particulates and some of the gasses in woodsmoke. The new EPA rules require stove makers to cut particulates in smoke by 77 percent effective today, and by 81 percent from the pre-1988 standard in 1990. Vermont Castings officials, wary of a patchwork of regulations in states concerned about winter haze, helped the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> devise the new rules, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimbell </PERSON>, the company's vice president for marketing. The new stoves meet the standards by burning wood more efficiently, <ORGANIZATION> Kimbell </ORGANIZATION> said, adding that the company has been working with a catalytic combuster designed to burn most of the woodsmoke. <PERSON> Syme </PERSON>, 50, who wore a straw hat and bow tie Thursday as he addressed the crowd of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> dignitaries, company employees and dealers who milled about among balloons, ale and other props under yellow-and-white-striped party tents. `` This is like a commencement,'' he said. `` It's as if we've had a fun time together these last four years in the ivy halls ... and I think we're on the threshold of a new and exciting future.''
