<HEAD>Abducted Child Returns Home with Parents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 2-year-old who was kidnapped as a baby and adopted by an Israeli couple returned home clutching her Brazilian parents and a teddy bear. Her mother said she would someday allow her child to decide if she wants to meet her adoptive parents in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, even though her lawyer said the <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> couple knew something was amiss in the adoption. <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON> arrived Thursday at <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>'s international airport with her parents, <PERSON> Rosilda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON>, on a flight from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. They had stopped there en route from <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. `` I feel as if <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> and I never had been separated, that she was never kidnapped,'' the child's mother told reporters while the brown-haired girl played with their tape recorders and microphones. The child also smiled and waved. The <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON>' two-year ordeal started Oct. 13, 1986, when their child, then 4 months old, was abducted from their home in the southern city of <LOCATION> Curitiba </LOCATION>. One year later, the child was located in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and the couple regained custody after a court battle with her adoptive parents. Asked if she would one day allow <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> to visit her former adoptive parents, Mrs. <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON> said: `` When she is older, I will tell her the whole story of what happened to her. Then she will be able to decide on her own whether or not she wants to see them again.'' Shortly after arriving back in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the child, dressed in a green jump suit, romped through the baggage-claim area, rode the conveyor belt and wheeled around a pushcart. Occasionally, she interrupted her play to embrace her parents. The family later boarded a plane for <LOCATION> Curitiba </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Parana </LOCATION> state authorities planned a big reception and meeting with Gov. <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Dias </PERSON>. At a brief news conference held in the airport's press room, Mrs. <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON>, looking tired but composed, held <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> on her lap and said, `` I never doubted I would be reunited with my daughter. It's a marvelous feeling having her back, and I owe it all to my faith in God, luck, persistence and the many people who helped me.'' Police say <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON>'s kidnapping was the work of one of many baby-trafficking rings that abduct or buy infants from mothers in poor areas and sell them for hefty profits to childless foreign couples. Adoption by foreigners is legal in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, but it is a time-consuming bureaucratic process that sometimes takes several years. With phony or even legitimate papers obtained through corrupt officials, the baby-trafficking rings can arrange an adoption within weeks, police say. The Israeli couple who adopted <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON>, <PERSON> Yaacov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Simone </PERSON> <PERSON> Turgeman </PERSON>, paid $ 25,000 to intermediaries but said they acted in good faith, believing the high fee and documents were legal. But <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuber </PERSON>, the Israeli lawyer who helped the Brazilian couple get their daughter back, said: `` The Turgemans may not have known <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> had been kidnapped, but they certainly knew something was fishy. They knew the documents were phony.'' <PERSON> Schuber </PERSON>, who accompanied <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> back to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, said: `` They had to know something was illegal about the whole thing. No one goes to <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> to adopt a Brazilian child and thinks it's all legal.'' Almost immediately after her abduction, <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> was taken across the border to neighboring <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, where she was handed over to the Turgemans. About one year afterward, <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> was located near <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. Her parents contacted Brazilian authorities for help in getting her back, and earlier this month, the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided she should be returned to her parents in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON> said that at first her relationship with the Turgemans `` was just fine. They seemed understanding and were willing to cooperate. But later the relationship deteriorated.'' She declined to say why. <PERSON> Olavo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Souza </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Curitiba </LOCATION> radio reporter who covered the story in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for more than a month, said the relationship soured when the Israeli couple `` tried to convince the Vasconceloses to abandon the idea of taking <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON> home.'' `` When they saw the Vasconceloses would not consider such a proposition, they filed an appeal in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to postpone <PERSON> Bruna </PERSON>'s return. But the court turned them down,'' <PERSON> Souza </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Vasconcelos </PERSON> said the Turgemans treated her daughter well. `` But the way they raised her was nothing special,'' she said. `` They did n't do anything I would not do.''
