<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A determined black bear with a sweet tooth forced its way into a <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> home and helped itself to a chocolate birthday cake, police said. It returned later for seconds. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> said nobody was at home Wednesday when the bear clawed and pushed its way in through a back door of her house in this town about 100 miles south of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>. When she returned, she said she found her bird feeder knocked over and animal droppings outside the door. Inside, a trash can had been knocked over and the cake, meant for her daughter's 23rd birthday, was gone. So was the bear. It left behind only the candles and plate. `` Actually, she said the bear was really nice in not tearing up the house,'' said Police Officer <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON>. The bear returned about midnight, and would not leave the area outside the house, <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> said. She called the police. `` I rolled up with my lights out, but the bear evidently heard the vehicle pull in,'' <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON> said. `` The bear either heard me or smelled me and split. It definitely came back for seconds.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City officials have pulled the plug _ at least temporarily _ on two entrepreneurs who want to reintroduce the electric rolling chair to <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s famed boardwalk. Antique wicker rolling chairs that now transport tourists down the wooden way are pushed by hand for a fee. But Ernest English and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> discovered that mechanical chairs were popular several decades ago, and want to restore them in an updated version. They recently bought all 100 dormant licenses for electrically propelled rolling chairs from the city. Then they created a prototype of a new chair _ a version that looks more like an enlongated, covered golf cart than the wicker original. That's when the rolling chair war began. `` It's a power play,'' English said. `` Rolling chairs can earn about $ 350 a day, so it's a money thing. I understand that over 40 people came in this week looking for electric chair licenses. We've become a commodity that everyone wants. <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s legal definition of a rolling chair, contained in a 1950 ordinance, is a wheeled vehicle for hire for the transportation of two or three people. A later ordinance restricts their length to 88 inches, or slightly more than seven feet. The prototype electric chair introduced by English and <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> is 10 feet long and seats five plus the driver. City officials pulled the partners' licenses Thursday, ordering the new contraption off the boardwalk after only four days in business. They plan to meet with the men next week. English, 30, and <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON>, 31, acknowledge their cart is controversial, and plan to redesign it to make it more conventional.
