<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices took a plunge today as the dollar continued its climb against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The dollar opened at 133.57 yen, up a strong 1.37 yen from the previous day's closing. It rose rapidly to end the week at 134.50 yen, up 2.30 from Thursday's finish. The dollar closed today at its highest level since Nov. 27, when it finished at 134.75 yen. It ranged between 133.55 and 134.60 yen today, with spot volume estimated at $ 9.8 billion. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, the market's main barometer, shed 265.87 points, or 0.95 percent, closing at 27,503.53. The loss came after a rally of 371.31 points over the previous two trading days. `` Share prices fell because the stock market was adjusting itself to the weaker yen,'' said a broker with a major securities firm who spoke on condition of anonymity. But he noted that activity was very heavy, with 2.6 billion shares traded in the first section. Volume was up from 2.5 billion shares traded on the first section Thursday. Among the issues posting sharp losses were steels, heavy industrials and electricals, the trader said. Also losing ground were constructions, nonferrous metals and textiles. Low-priced issues, including trading houses and shippings, held on to earlier gains, traders said. Foreign exchange dealers said the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market seemed to be testing whether <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s central bank would take any action to stem the dollar's rise. `` Right now it is unclear how far the government is willing to let the dollar go,'' said an exchange dealer with a major commercial bank. `` But it is rumored that Finance Minister -LRB- <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> sees the 138-yen level as acceptable.'' The trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he did not believe the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> had stepped into the market today to stem the yen's slide. The central bank does not comment officially on its market interventions. Earlier this week, Japanese monetary authorities, including <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, said the central bank would use market intervention if necessary to brake the dollar's upswing.
