peech, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> recalled how earlier economic reforms in the 1950s and 1960s were `` swallowed up'' because there was no accompanying political change. His `` perestroika'' could go the same way without political reform, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> indicated. `` Doubt, lack of confidence, that would be the greatest gifts to the opponents of perestroika,'' he said. `` Socialism, <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, that is the creative activity of the masses,'' he said. `` But that activity will die unless we reform the political system.'' Earlier, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> broke into a speech by a delegate who said people feel party stalwarts can not work under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms if they previously carried out the now-discredited policies of <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who died in 1982. `` Maybe you have some concrete suggestions?'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asked delegate <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Melnikov </PERSON> from his position on the dais. `` We're sitting here and do n't know: Is he talking about me, or somebody else? `` I was referring first of all to <PERSON> Comrade </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON>, and to <PERSON> Comrades </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>,'' replied <PERSON> Melnikov </PERSON>, head of the party in the <LOCATION> Komi </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. The exchange was shown on national television in an extremely rare attack on named members of the ruling Politburo. Such criticism has not surfaced despite the recent growing independence of the Soviet press. <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> and another Politburo member, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON>, have been members of the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> since the 1960s. <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, one of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s foremost experts on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> affairs, has headed the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> since 1967. There are at least two delegates with the surname <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON>. One is <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda since 1976.
