<HEAD>Vietnamese Officer Describes Guerrilla Attacks in Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas planted explosives that injured 33 people in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s capital last year and tried to blow up a strategic bridge there in 1984, a Vietnamese army officer said today. Col. <PERSON> Dinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Nhu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON>, commander of an elite unit assigned to protect <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, provided a rare disclosure of guerrilla infiltrations. But he said the capital has been very secure since <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978 and set up a pro-Vietnamese government. He dismissed the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the main guerrilla infiltrators, as `` leftovers of an army that was beaten up and became bandits.'' <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said the last members of his unit, 1,200 men, returned home on June 6 as part of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s plan to withdraw 50,000 troops, or half its force in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, by the end of the year. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says its military command and all military advisers returned home on Thursday, turning responsibility for the war over to <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> officers. About 50,000 Cambodians, according to official count, turned out on the streets of their capital as about 300 Vietnamese commanders left <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> and flew to <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, formerly <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> acknowledged it lost 25,000 men in the war, but most of the fighting was away from the capital. <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said that no Vietnamese soldiers had been killed in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> since he took up his post in January 1979. There were no major attacks on the city and most intrusions were on its outskirts, he said. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s army rarely provides details of operations. The only reports of guerrilla infiltration into <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> have come from highly exaggerated <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> claims or sketchy accounts from a few Western aid officials. Fanatic <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> communists killed millions of people when they ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> from 1975 until the Vietnamese invasion. <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> spoke with foreign journalists invited to cover the Vietnamese pullout. He said the worst period was from March 23 to July 20 last year when <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> agents planted 44 Chinese-made explosives on the outskirts of the city. The plastic-covered bombs, about 4 inches in diameter and 1 -LCB- inches wide, exploded when touched, he said. `` The intention was to scare people,'' he said. `` They laid the explosives in the people's water tanks, bus terminals, staircases of people's houses, or on the road.'' <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said 33 people, all civilians, were wounded, including six Vietnamese living in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The leader of the saboteurs, a <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> battalion commander, was sentenced to death and another suspect, a <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> underground activist, sentenced to life imprisonment, <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said. Authorities also captured 15 others whom the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> had paid $ 500 for each bomb they placed, he said. They received shorter jail terms or were put in political `` re-education'' camps. He said the second most serious attack was the firing of two H-12 rockets into the city on Dec. 27, 1986. Both crashed into paddy fields, causing no injuries, and a <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> operative who launched the rockets was captured, he said. <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> also said six <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> operatives were caught in an abortive plot to blow up the <LOCATION> Son </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ngoc </LOCATION> <LOCATION> bridge </LOCATION>, the capital's biggest, which links its eastern and western sectors The plot was organized in 1983 and explosives were to be planted in early 1984, he said. <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said the chief plotter, <PERSON> Mon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ly </PERSON>, was sentenced to death and the five others were given prison terms or probation. While <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said guerrilla-related incidents in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> were declining, he did not discount claims by diplomats that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> was lying low to prepare for attacks in 1990, when <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says its last soldiers will leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He said some Cambodians in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> reacted to this year's pullout with apprehension about the return of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> said guerrillas also conduct limited psychological warfare in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, distributing handwritten leaflets saying `` that Khmer -LRB- Cambodians -RRB- should not fight Khmer. The Khmer should fight the Vietnamese.'' The Vietnamese colonel said military intelligence indicated the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> exaggerated its strength in referring to `` Division 18,'' the unit that was behind the 1986 rocket attack and the 1987 explosions. `` A division should have about 10,000 soldiers,'' he said. `` But they have only 250 people and call themselves a division. Nonsense. They do n't have any strategy or tactics.''
