<HEAD>Officials Deny Police Killed Pollution Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials today denied Western reports that police killed several peasants and brutally beat others who tried to stop the release of polluted water from a reservoir near <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> late Thursday issued the first official report of the June 21 protest during which peasants tried to stop a petrochemical company from releasing contaminated waste water from a reservoir into a local stream. The peasants said the water would poison their wells and crops. Officials said the water level in the reservoir had risen too high and that there was danger of flooding. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuoseng </PERSON>, local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> secretary, criticized foreign reporting of the protest and accused Western reporters of violating government regulations this week when they visited the reservoir in <LOCATION> Guce </LOCATION> village. Authorities there turned away some Western reporters this week and confiscated film and audio tapes. Guce, which is under the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> municipal administration, is 37 miles southwest of the city center. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> cited the same regulation that was used last October to expel 14 Western reporters from <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> following violent pro-independence, anti-Chinese riots by Tibetans in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>. The regulation requires foreign reporters to apply for permission when traveling to report in areas open to foreigners. Reporters previously had interpreted it to apply to places outside <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and officials have never before invoked it in greater <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The new interpretation would significantly widen the scope of the regulation and severely limit foreign reporting in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. At today's news conference, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said the July 21 protest was much smaller than peasant witnesses have said. He denied witness accounts that thousands of armed police were brought in and scores of peasants were badly hurt. Villagers told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that more than 1,500 farmers clashed with at least 2,000 armed police, and 60 to 70 protestors were seriously injured when police beat them with nightsticks and used electric cattle prods. Some villagers told Western reporters that three people were killed, but those who spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> said they could not confirm any deaths. `` What you're talking about is what a small number of people are saying. I was at the site. I can assure you that there were no more than 500 farmers,'' <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said. He said about 200 unarmed local police were at the scene. He denied that anyone was killed or seriously injured, but said some people might have been slightly hurt during the scuffle. Villagers also said 150 people were arrested the day of the protest, and that 10 remained in custody, but <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said only five people were being interrogated. He said they have not been formally arrested or charged. He did not say if others had been detained and released. The waste stored in the Niukou Reservoir came from the state-owned <ORGANIZATION> Yanshan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petrochemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said it was produced after the plant dismantled its old waste treatment equipment and before it had installed new equipment <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said he did not know what chemicals were in the water or what affect they could have on human health and crops. By mid-June, the water in the reservoir had risen to a dangerous level and had to be released to avoid flooding, he said. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> is having its annual rainy season. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said the petrochemical company will compensate the farmers for all losses they suffer in their summer wheat harvest and for 60 percent of losses of their autumn grain crop.
