<HEAD>Report: Ford Offers Settlement In Fatal Church Bus Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has offered out-of-court settlements of less than $ 1 million to each of the families of the 24 children killed in a fiery May 14 church bus crash, a newspaper reported today. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which made the bus chassis, also offered payments to the estates of the three adults who died in the accident near <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, and to the 40 survivors, based on the severity of their injuries, The <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported today, attributing the information to unidentified lawyers. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> told the newspaper that `` delicate'' negotiations were under way, but would not comment on whether a settlement had been offered. Lawyer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>, who represents the families of two of the dead children, said a settlement was being offered by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and all manufacturers responsible for producing the bus, including <ORGANIZATION> Sheller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which assembled it. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> declined to disclose the size of the offers, but described them as `` attractive financially'' to the families and also a good deal for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sheller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman did not return phone calls seeking comment, the newspaper reported. Lawyer <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Skeeters </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Radcliff firm of <ORGANIZATION> Skeeters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, which is representing most of the remaining plaintiffs, refused to confirm or deny that an offer had been made. Lawyers who have handled similar cases told the <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> it would be highly unusual, if not unprecedented, for such a major case to be settled so quickly, before lawsuits were even filed. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Coale </PERSON>, who represents one family and has been active in several air-disaster cases, said it would be `` unconscionable'' to settle so quickly without exploring whether <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> might be liable for punitive damages. He predicted the cases might be worth as much as $ 120 million. <PERSON> Coale </PERSON>, who represents the parents of <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fair </PERSON>, who was killed in the crash, said his client intended to take <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to trial even if all other plaintiffs settle out of court, although he acknowledged it would be difficult for one client to finance such a battle. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said he would present the bus makers' proposal today to his clients, the parents of <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunnallee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON>. In <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>'s view, the families must decide between accepting the offers, which he called `` a sure thing,'' or the `` reality of fighting one of the largest corporations in the nation for four or five years.'' While he described the offers as attractive, he said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> might be forced to pay $ 60 million to $ 70 million for compensatory damages alone if the case is tried. The total value of the proposed settlement offer is `` nowhere close to that,'' he said. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> also said his clients, whom he described as more interested in bus-safety reforms than money, also might refuse to accept <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s stipulation that settlement values be kept secret. The converted school bus, owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Radcliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, was returning 67 people _ mostly children _ to the church after a day at the <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> amusement park near <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. Police say the accident was caused by a drunken driver traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71. However, investigators have said other factors combined to increase the loss of life, including the bus' lone rear exit door and crowded conditions inside. Authorities also cited the bus' gas tank, which ruptured and burst into flames. The resulting smoke was blamed for all 27 deaths. The bus was apparently one of the last manufactured in 1977 before a new federal rule required bus fuel tanks be sheathed in protective cages.
