<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-AIDSNotification     07-01 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-AIDS Notification,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partner-Notification Plans Exist In All States, CDC Finds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AMA-AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Procedures to warn the sex or drug-sharing partners of people infected with AIDS virus are now under way in every state, according to a new report from the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that all 50 states encourage partner notification, through programs by which infected people are urged to inform partners with whom they have had sex or shared needles. Forty-eight states have in place `` referral on request'' programs to inform partners when an AIDS-infected patient asks them to. The other two _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> _ have programs to inform partners in certain case, such as women of childbearing age or rape victims. In addition, a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law going into effect today specifies that health authorities may contact spouses, sex partners or other parties for disclosure purposes after first trying to inform the patient that they plan to do so. AIDS, caused by a virus, is transmitted chiefly through sex or contaminated drug needles. Partner notification, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted, has been a key part of efforts to fight sexually transmitted diseases since the advent of penicillin to treat syphilis in the 1940s. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> recommends that AIDS-infected people `` should be instructed in how to notify their partners and to refer them for counseling and testing.'' The agency also recommends that if infected people can not or will not get their partners to seek counseling, `` physicians or health department personnel should use confidential procedures to assure that the partners are notified.'' `` All the states are giving counseling to patients about the need to inform their sex partners and needle-sharing partners,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Toomey </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> researcher. Having a third party notify people at risk `` has been shown to be effective, but costly,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. Because of limits on money and other resources, having patients inform their own partners `` has played an increasingly important role.'' In four of the states offering outside notification of sex or drug partners _ <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> _ the percentage of partners identified through the programs who agreed to AIDS tests and showed signs of infection ranged from 14 to 39 percent, Ms. <PERSON> Toomey </PERSON> said. `` By identifying such individuals, the partner-notification process can target risk-reduction messages to those at greatest risk of acquiring or transmitting infection,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. More than 65,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>; 88 percent have occurred among homosexual males or injectible drug abusers, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. More than 37,000 patients have already died.
</TEXT>
