<HEAD>Suspected Kidnapper Says He Planned Abduction For Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The suspect in the country's only known fatal kidnap case said today he picked his victim, a Dutch tycoon, at random and then spent two months planning the abduction. <PERSON> Ferdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON>, 45, said at his trial here that he began mapping out the abduction of grocery baron <PERSON> Gerrit-Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> in July 1987. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> was kidnapped Sept. 9, and his body was found April 4. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> said he chose his victim at random. His lawyer, <PERSON> Johannes </PERSON> <PERSON> Weermeijer </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> `` knew Mr. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> from the telephone directory.'' There was no immediate word on the motive for the abduction. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s relatives paid $ 8 million ransom. The only other testimony scheduled to be given was that of a forensic psychiatrist who has examined the suspect extensively. Under Dutch trial practice, the hearing of witnesses is unusual. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> has confessed that he abducted and killed <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>. If found guilty, he could be sentenced to life in prison. Local press reports indicated that the psychiatric report claimed that at the time of the abduction, <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> bore only `` limited responsibility'' for his deeds. If the court accepted that claim, it could impose a limited jail sentence followed by confinement in an institution for the criminally insane. The soft-spoken <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> is an unemployed business consultant with an engineering degree from a Dutch university. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> told court president Ms. C.A. <PERSON> Terwee-Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Holten </PERSON> that he shot and killed <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> on the day of his kidnapping in a forest near <LOCATION> Renkum </LOCATION>, in the eastern <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>, vice president of the multimillion-dollar <ORGANIZATION> Ahold </ORGANIZATION> retail concern, was abducted from his sprawling villa in <LOCATION> Bloemendaal </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> Haarlem </LOCATION>'s affluent suburbs, while on his way to a dental appointment. On April 4, <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s body was dug up from a forest in the eastern <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> after police arrested <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON>. Their arrest came after a bank employee discovered a 250-gilder note from the ransom payment.
