<HEAD>First U.S. Missile Inspectors Under Treaty Going to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> inspectors assigned to verify Soviet compliance with the treaty to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear weapons left for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> today. Their Soviet counterparts arrive in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> tonight. The two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspection teams, each comprised of 10 experts, traveled from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rhein-Main </LOCATION> Air Base. They were led by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brig </ORGANIZATION>. Gen. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Lojoie </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which was formed Jan. 15, 1988 after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed the <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> treaty in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. That accord eliminated ground-based short - and medium-range missiles `` We all feel this is a historic mission,'' <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> told reporters before boarding a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Its impact on international relations can not be underestimated. We are proud to be a part of this important moment in history.'' <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> said one team would travel to the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Votkinsk </LOCATION>, the site of a plant that formerly built the Soviets' SS-20 missiles The SS-20s are covered by the treaty, along with <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-built </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 missiles and cruise missiles based in western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team must tell the Soviets within 48 hours after arrival where it intends to begin conducting inspections, <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> said. He did not disclose which site that would be. `` We're going in with the attitude ` Trust everybody, but always cut the cards,''' <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> said. The general said that although there are 1,800 missiles whose destruction must be checked, other related items _ including storage and transport missile containers and special hauling vehicles _ bring the actual number of items to be inspected to at least 5,000. The inspection teams will be checking for numbers of missiles, and individual components will be measured and weighed under the inspection process agreed upon with the Soviets, said <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON>. In the next two months, the inspectors will visit 126 sites in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, including 33 in eastern <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> said. The Soviets will inspect 26 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, including 11 in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officials. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> teams include linguists and specialists in nuclear missiles. Although the inspection teams are comprised of members of all branches of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military and civilian government employees, the inspection agreement calls for all of them to wear civilian clothes during their stay in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> commander Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> said he was confident the verification arrangements would work. He said he had been surprised at the openness the Soviets have shown in the visits to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> elimination sites so far.
