<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     07-01 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Bill To Strengthen Residential Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government proposed legislation today that would strengthen residential segregation but also would allow creation of the first legal multi-racial neighborhoods. Government opponents condemned the three proposed measures, saying they would force the evictions of thousands of blacks now living peacefully but illegally in `` whites only'' areas. `` The government indicates once again its absolute obsession with skin color as a norm on which to base <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s political, social and economic life,'' said the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON>, member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, called the measures `` so harsh and so brutal'' that up to 200,000 blacks could be evicted on short notice. Under the Group Areas Act, all residential areas are segregated by race. However, thousands of non-whites are living illegally in neighborhoods designated for whites in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and other urban areas. One of the proposed measures, the Group Areas Amendment Bill, would make it easier to confiscate property and to evict and prosecute people living in areas not designated for their race group. The maximum fine for a person living outside his group area would be increased from $ 175 to $ 4,300. The maximum prison sentence would be increased from two years to five years. The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old Group Areas Act in recent years, angering conservative whites opposed to integrated neighborhoods. The proposed bill is widely seen as an accommodation to right-wing whites prior to nationwide municipal elections in October. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> favors gradual race reform but says it is committed to preserving white `` group rights'' such as segregated schools and neighborhoods. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has dominated South African politics for 40 years but has been losing ground to the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes all concessions to the nation's 26 million black majority. Under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s system of apartheid, blacks have no vote in national affairs. A second proposed bill, the Free Settlement Areas Bill, would allow creation of residential areas open to all races. But before such areas could be established, a government committee would check `` the necessity or desirability'' of an area being opened to all races. A third bill would set up guidelines for multi-racial political participation by residents in `` open areas.'' The three bills are to be debated in the next session of Parliament in August.
</TEXT>
