<HEAD>Small `Star Wars' Rocket Engine Successfully Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aerospace experts developing `` Star Wars'' technology have successfully tested a tiny, 2-ounce rocket engine designed to power satellite-based missile killers. The engine tested at <ORGANIZATION> Rocketdyne </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Susana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Field </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday is slated for use as a directional thruster for a space-based interceptor in the Strategic Defense Initiative program. The goal is to neutralize incoming enemy nuclear missiles before they re-enter the atmosphere by using lasers and interceptor rockets. The new engine, dubbed by designers as the most efficient in the free world, would guide the interceptor from its base on a satellite toward an approaching nuclear missile. The missile would be destroyed on impact. Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Space Division, <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rocketdyne </ORGANIZATION> called the test successful, praising the engine's weight-to-thrust ratio, a measure of its power and efficiency. Thrust is the forward force produced in reaction to gases escaping rearward from the engine. `` The engines we were running with around five years ago were 1-to-20,'' said <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunch </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Rocketdyne </ORGANIZATION> engineer in the space-based interceptor, or SABIR, program. The tiny engine tested has a weight-to-thrust ratio of 1-to-1 ,200, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Patota </PERSON>, engineer in charge of the test area The engine was fired, or pulsed, for five milliseconds and then was shut off for 1 @ 10 of a second. This cycle was repeated dozens of times during each of the three testings. The result sounded like machine gun fire. The interceptor rockets would be equipped with four of the tested engines and four smaller thrusters.
