<FIRST>u a PM-CopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0514 07-01 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Copter Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Report Blames Human, Design Problems for Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with news conference; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede EVANSVILLE, Ind.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Human error and design flaws contributed to the collision of two Army helicopters that killed 17 soldiers during night training at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>, according to a report released today. `` Human error-pilot error is presumed to be the cause of this mishap,'' said the report released at a news conference. But the report added, `` Because the accident was fatal to the crew of both aircraft, it is impossible to determine exactly what caused the two aircraft to fly into each other.'' The report said one of the two UH-60 <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION> did not have its anti-collision strobe turned on as required at the time of the March 8 accident. The report also cited other factors, including limited pilot training using night-vision goggles and exterior and interior design flaws of the Black Hawk. The report said there was no evidence of a mechanical malfunction. `` There should be no action taken against anyone as no foundation for negligence can be established,'' the report said. `` The accident was not due to lack of diligence, nor unreasonable or unprofessional conduct.'' The accident occurred when a Black Hawk returning from a solo instruction flight collided with the lead helicopter in a formation of three returning from a mission to pick up soldiers in the field. The lead helicopter, struck broadside, carried 13 soldiers; the other craft carried four. All were killed. The other two helicopters were not damaged and landed safely. The 17 victims belonged to the 101st Airborne Division at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>. The investigation concluded the collision `` was the result of the two air crews' being unable to see each other in the final moments of flight,'' according to a statement read by Maj. <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON>, public-affairs officer at <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>. `` Restrictions to vision caused by door posts and structural components of the aircraft and the limited field of view of the night vision goggles being used by both crews hampered their ability to see and avoid each,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. The lights on the helicopter leading the formation could `` very easily have been obscured and blended into'' city lights, <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. Crew members on the undamaged helicopters said there was little warning that another helicopter was approaching. `` Up to the point of impact, the missions were formed just as briefed,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Shockney </PERSON>, pilot of the third helicopter, told investigators the lone helicopter did not have its anti-collision strobe on. The strobe is attached to the front of the Black Hawk. `` That is the one thing that really catches your eyes under goggles,'' he said. `` If he would have had his anti-collision light on, we would have seen him for miles and miles.'' Investigators theorize the crew forgot to turn the anti-collision strobe light on after a fuel stop, the report said. Compounding the problem, the report said, was the lack of lighting on the helicopters. The report said the number and size of position lights on the outside of the $ 4.6 million Black Hawk are inadequate. Moreover, the pilot and co-pilot of the incoming helicopter could have been tired, the report said.
</TEXT>
