<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has given thousands of foreign sugar cane workers an opportunity to qualify for permanent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> resident status under a program for seasonal farm workers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to accept applications from sugar cane workers to obtain legal resident status under streamlined procedures to accommodate a Nov. 1 deadline. Under the 1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act, seasonal workers have that date to file applications to qualify for the program. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> also ordered <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> to grant work authorization papers to the applicants and barred the agency from initiating deportation proceedings against those individuals. `` Equity demands that these sugar cane workers be afforded an opportunity to stay in the country pending the final outcome regarding the status of sugar cane'' in the program for seasonal workers, <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>, who ruled in April that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had not justified excluding sugar cane harvesters from the program, chided <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> for the continuing delay in drafting new regulations. He gave <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> until July 11 to propose the new regulations and set an August 19 deadline for issuing the final rule. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> could still issue regulations that exclude sugar cane harvesters from the program, but the agency would have to give <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> further justification for its decision. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> had sought to issue its new regulations in September, but <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said further delays would not give the workers enough time to qualify for legal status if the department ultimately decided they could participate in the program. `` The court views with skepticism ... -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- claims that, despite at least three drafts which have been rejected, the agency still is grappling with the drafting of the regulation,'' <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said.
