<HEAD>Rain Helps Plains Farmers, Floods Some Fields</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with rain amounts today,
Wisconsin legislature, record low temps, Iowa rain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Good Harvest, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Heavy rain soaked the central Plains today, bringing new life to wilting crops and flooding parts of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, but some farmers complained that the wet weather was too little, too late. `` It's too late for this corn even if it does rain,'' said <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> farmer <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Limon </PERSON>, edging into chest-high stalks that should be 3 feet higher by now. The struggling ears were pale; the kernels were widely spaced. `` You can hear it rattle when the wind blows. And that's a bad sign,'' <PERSON> Limon </PERSON> said Thursday hours before scattered rain fell on the state. `` But we're thankful. It could be no ears at all.'' A bill to guarantee up to $ 35 million in loans to help farmers suffering through the drought was passed Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and sent to the governor. It would provide about 3,500 potential loans to farmers whose debts totaled 40 percent of their assets. Maximum loans would be $ 10,000 for up to three years at 6 percent interest. Widespread rain fell Thursday night and early today from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Chanute </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, got 2.14 inches in the six hours up to 7 a.m. and 2.02 inches fell at <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. But forecasters cautioned that the drought continues. `` The indications are that this is a temporary interlude,'' said <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, where 3.72 inches fell Wednesday and early Thursday. That city got an additional 1.83 inches today. `` Over the long haul, we expect to return to the dry, hot weather. Ten days from now, people will be needing water again.'' The rain came too late to help the wheat crop, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordquist </PERSON>, crop production specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska-Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> and Extension Center in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION>. One example of the shortfall in precipitation is <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillaker </PERSON>, acting state climatologist, said final statistics for the first six months of the year are expected to show average state rainfall came to 7.45 inches, driest on record, including more than 2 inches earlier this week in some areas. Normal rainfall in that period is 15.72 inches. For some it was not only too late, but too much. Fields, roads and bridges in northeastern <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> were under up to 5 feet of water Thursday. The heaviest rain reported was 12 inches in <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>. About 20 <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> residents had to be evacuated _ some by boat _ because of flooding, county authorities said. `` I knew it was raining when I went to sleep, and when I woke up water was rushing in the front door,'' said resident <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Silvers </PERSON>. `` I panicked and grabbed everything I could and started yelling at my neighbor across the street to see if she was OK.'' The water washed away large chunks of asphalt from county roads and uprooted fields of crops made fragile by the heat and drought Residents were allowed back in their homes Thursday. Thunderstorms brought cooler temperatures to the Plains and a cold front pushed temperatures to record lows today around the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Elkins, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, got down to a brisk 32 degrees But the heat wave that had gripped the Midwest claimed another victim Thursday. An 80-year-old <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> man died of dehydration three days after he and his wife were found in a wheat field. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Archer </PERSON> died at a <LOCATION> Cordell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, hospital after attempts to rehydrate him failed, said <LOCATION> Washita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> undersheriff <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazureka </PERSON>. His wife, <PERSON> Rhoda </PERSON>, 77, died earlier after collapsing of heat exhaustion last weekend. In <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, an autopsy Thursday on a 77-year-old woman found dead in her home revealed she died of heatstroke. The body of <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> was found Wednesday as temperatures in Mobile hovered in the 90s.
