<HEAD>Police Move On Disputed Land Squatters, Communist Guards Help Them
Over Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police today chased nearly 200 squatters from a disputed piece of land near the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall after a monthlong struggle that pitted environmentalists against city developers. When the removal order came, the squatters found an unusual escape route _ over the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> into the city's Communist side. East German border guards helped them over the barrier, which divides the city of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> into Allied and Communist sectors. Most of the estimated 186 environmentalists who fled to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> had returned to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> by noon. Nine protesters were arrested in the raid. Eight have since been released, police said. The demonstrators were protesting plans to build a highway through a park nearby. When more than 900 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police moved in to clear the area, nearly 200 protesters were already sitting on the 13-foot-high wall. They earlier declared that they would seek `` political asylum'' in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> if West German police tried to rout them. East German guards backed trucks up to the eastern side of the wall to make it easier for the environmentalists to jump down and escape the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police. One smiling East German guard even helped one of the protesters by pulling his bicycle over the wall. The action to clear the squatters from the 10-acre piece of property known as the `` Lenne Triangle'' occurred after it formally came under <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s control one minute after midnight. It was handed over under the terms of a deal worked out with <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> this year. The protesters occupied the area on May 26 and quickly set up a shantytown and erected barriers to protect them from police charges. The property has been the scene of frequent violent skirmishes between police and demonstrators. Protesters often attacked police with bottles, stones and Molotov cocktails, and officers responded with tear gas and water cannons. Police could not legally enter the property until it came under <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> control.
