<HEAD>With PM-Romania-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament today condemned a Romanian plan to resettle ethnic Hungarians and called on <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> to reconsider the move. The resolution made no reference to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s decision this week to close a Hungarian consulate and expell its staff. It also did n't mention the order to close a Hungarian cultural center in the Romanian capital <PERSON> Matyas </PERSON> <PERSON> Szueroes </PERSON>, head of the foreign relations committee that drafted the document, appealed to Hungarians `` not to yield to emotions'' regarding the `` disquieting developments reported from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> maintains the program of moving residents of 7,000 villages to new agricultural-industrial centers would destroy ethnic Hungarian culture and tradition in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> says it would help villagers by providing services now enjoyed only in cities. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s treatment of its 1.7 million Hungarian residents has long been a sticky issue between the two <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact allies. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> claims the Hungarian minority is discriminated against. <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> says <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s criticism is interference in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s internal affairs <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Tuesday closed <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s consulate in <LOCATION> Cluj </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>, home to most of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s ethnic Hungarians, to protest a demonstration by 50,000 people in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> against the resettlement program. <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> also insisted that the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> move out of rooms rented for a cultural center. Official media in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> reported that Romanian authorities also were sending back some Hungarian travelers without giving any reason for the move. A Hungarian border official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said today there was no official ban. The parliamentary document, which is to be sent to the Romanian legislature, said the beginning of the Romanian program would further weaken Hungarian-Romanian relations. The document said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> hoped <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> `` would reexamine its ... plans and will refrain from their implementation.'' `` This would remove an important obstacle to the rapprochement between the Hungarian and <LOCATION> Romanian </LOCATION> people,'' the document said. On Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> appealed for dialogue with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who is also premier, said the tension was temporary and warned against drawing long-term conclusions. He told Western journalists he would go ahead with a planned visit to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> because `` if we do n't talk to each other we can not understand each other.'' No date for the trip has been announced, but it is believed <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> will go to <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> after visits in July to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. On Thursday, a Hungarian diplomat in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> said <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> had declared <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s cultural center in the Romanian capital closed and ordered the embassy to vacate the building. The cultural center was never issued a permit to start operation and has been used as a storage for the embassy in recent years.
