<HEAD>Ancient Ethnic Strife Stymies East European Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 4th graf pvs: `Romania's decision..,' to
UDPATE with Hungarian parliament action. Pick up 5th graf pvs:
`Hungary maintains...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s move to shut down a Hungarian consulate was unprecedented in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance and shows how historically rooted ethnic strife can foul up Soviet-led attempts to forge unity in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Seventy years after <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> gained the region of <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, the two neighbors are still bickering over treatment of the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians who live in the fictional homeland of Count Dracula. In the past two years, the dispute has escalated sharply, pointing up the difference between <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s reform-minded communism and the inflexible regime of <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, which is increasingly isolated even among its East bloc allies. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s decision Tuesday to close the general consulate in <LOCATION> Cluj-Napoca </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> came in retaliation for an anti-Romanian rally in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, the Hungarian capital, on Monday night. About 50,000 Hungarians protested <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s plans to destroy 7,000 Romanian villages, including hundreds of Hungarian communities. Today, the Hungarian parliament condemned the resettlement plan and urged <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> to reconsider the move. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> maintains the plan would destroy the Hungarians' cultural heritage and ultimately wipe out Hungarian and other minorities in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> Romanian officials said the villages to be razed by the year 2000 would be replaced by agricultural-industrial centers designed to remove differences between country and city dwellers. Hungarian officials at a mass meeting on <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>'s Heroes Square Monday evening said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> probably will seek international support to pressure <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to cancel the project. But <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> on Tuesday rejected Hungarian protests as `` nationalistic, chauvinistic, anti-Romanian and anti-Socialist.'' <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s address indicated that relations have reached their lowest ebb in post-war communist history. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> long has complained about acts of official discrimination against its Hungarian minority across the border and asserted that its people are denied important cultural and ethnic rights. The ethnic Hungarians, known in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> as Magyars, live in a 21,000-square-mile area of some of the most picturesque mountain and farm land in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION>. The land was under Hungarian control for nine centuries but was given to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Dec. 1, 1919, as part of the dismemberment of the Austro-Hungarian empire after World War I. Nazi dictator <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> returned much of the land to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> during World War II in appreciation of the loyalty of the country's ruler, Adm. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Horthy </PERSON> After the war the Allies gave <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> back to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. The Romanians support their claim to the land by arguing that Romanized Dacians, their apparent ancestors, stayed in the area after the Romans withdrew from what is now <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> in the 3rd century A.D. But Hungarian scholars maintain the Dacians withdrew along with their Roman protectors south of the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> river and that the Magyars found a largely empty country when they drifted in from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> in the 9th century. <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> relinquished its claim to <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> by signing the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreements recognizing post-war borders, but the Hungarian government and people remain deeply interested in the area's Hungarian minority. `` Treatment of national minorities in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> is synonymous with South African apartheid,'' Hungarian poet <PERSON> Gyula </PERSON> <PERSON> Illyes </PERSON> said 10 years ago. The Romanian government says its treatment of the Hungarian and German minorities is fair. It accuses <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> of chauvinism and interfererence in its internal affairs and says <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is trying to regain <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>. Last April, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> strongly criticized <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> for decreeing that Romanian-language place names must be used for cities and villages traditionally known to the country's ethnic minorities in their own language. In March, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> took the unprecedented action of approving about $ 6 million to help thousands of ethnic Hungarian refugees who have fled the shortages and harsh living conditions in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. The refugees, believed to number up to 20,000 now, also include several hundred Romanian speakers who are seeking to settle in the West.
</TEXT>
