<HEAD>Austrian President Withdraws Lawsuit Against WJC President Bronfman
^Eds: SUBS 3rd graf: `First, the...,' to CORRECT attribution to
Christian. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Second, the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> today withdrew a slander suit filed against <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a spokesman said. <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> last year called <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> `` part and parcel of the Nazi killing machine.'' Spokesman <PERSON> Gerold </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> cited three reasons for the move in a letter sent to the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> prosecutor's office. `` First, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has refused legal assistance, which is in contrast to international legal norms,'' and this ruled out a quick court action, <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> said. `` Second, the -LRB- international -RRB- commission of historians, private undertakings as well as international historians have determined <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s personal innocence. `` Third, there is an endeavor -LRB- on the part of the president -RRB- to contribute to calming down and reconciliation,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in December 1987 that it has evidence of <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s complicity in the transfer of civilian prisoners to the Nazi SS for exploitation in labor camps during World War II, the deportations of Jews from <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> islands to concentration or death camps, the execution of Allied prisoners and the execution of hostages and other civilians. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied wrongdoing. <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> stopped the suit also `` to calm things down for <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, because the country always has priority over personal matters.'' It was believed that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> decided to stop legal proceedings against <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> because there was virtually no chance for the court action ever to take place in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and even less chance that it would take place in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. With the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> unwilling to cooperate by having <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> testify in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court, and with <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> refusing to appear in an Austrian court, the lawsuit might never have been resolved. A report issued by an international commission of historians in February did not say if <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was involved in wartime atrocities but it made clear that as an intelligence officer in the German army, he was aware of them and did nothing to prevent them. The document seriousl questioned <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s integrity and led to widespread calls for his resignation, but the Austrian head of state refused to comply, insisting that the historians had cleared him of all charges. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> called on the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> prosecutor's office to sue <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> on May 7, 1987, two days after the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> president said he was `` part and parcel of the Nazi killing machine'' while serving in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> during the war. According to a presidential statement issued at the time, the lawsuit was also based on a comment by <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> who reportedly said if <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> `` has any patriotism in his soul whatsoever, his doctors would find reasons for him to resign his post.'' The third <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> comment cited by the president said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s `` misdeeds and his lying about his past'' were so obvious that it would be `` almost a crime against humanity to have very much to do with this man.''
