<HEAD>Poles Buy Unrationed Gas for First Time in Seven Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gasoline stations across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Friday struggled to cope with demand when gasoline without ration coupons went on sale legally for the first time since 1981. Customers at gasoline station No. 560 on Silver Street in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> waited an average of four hours in the hot sun to pay $ 2.69 a gallon, compared with the ration price of $ 1.58 a gallon. By midday, station manager <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnuszewski </PERSON> and his co-workers had pumped as much gasoline as they normally had in an entire day when the station sold rationed gasoline. Faces fell when a young man asked for 36.4 gallons at a cost of $ 98, about the average monthly wage. He filled his car and six big canisters, enduring hostile comments from fellow customers. At noon, a truck delivered more gas, reassuring those at the end of the 120-car line monitored by police to prevent double parking. The primarily male clientele read, picnicked, and played cards while waiting. The delivery driver brought word that four more gas stations would sell the unrationed gas, in addition to the two stations initially authorized for <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, a city of 1.5 million people. Some of the customers made a mad dash for the newly added stations. `` People are satisfied because they can at least get gasoline now,'' said <PERSON> Magnuszewski </PERSON>. State-run TV reported the new regulations and said customers interviewed had thanked the state gas monopoly for the opportunity to buy unrationed gas. The impatient customers at station No. 560 seemed to think otherwise. `` It's a bad idea _ a scandal. It's very uncomfortable to stand in this crowd of machines. I see the crowd and I do n't want to stand in line,'' said <PERSON> Krzystof </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>. He ultimately took a place in line. Some people feared the new regulations are a government ruse to raise prices even further. The government announced the regulations Tuesday. The Central Oil Products Monopoly initially planned to make the unrationed gasoline available at 64 gas stations nationwide. The State Monopolys' director <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Szewczyk </PERSON> said about 60 million gallons non-rationed gasoline would be sold at the higher price this year, less than 10 percent of all gasoline to be sold in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and that if demand exceeded supply the price would be raised. A sufficient supply of gas is a constant concern for Polish car owners. Under current regulations, every private car owner receives a monthly gas ration based on the car size. Owners of small cars are entitled to 6.2 gallons, while those with medium and large cars can get 9.4 gallons. Additional gasoline could be purchased on a black-market basis at some stations, but even that source does not meet demand. The government introduced rationing in mid-1981 when panic buying during the Solidarity period resulted in periodic shortages. Most of the oil <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> needs to manufacture gasoline comes from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> which has been reluctant to increase supplies to its East bloc allies, especially now that it too faces energy shortages. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> lacks hard currency to buy much crude on the world market.
