n tour in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> Wednesday. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Thursday in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, that he has shared ideas with Central American leaders on a diplomatic solution to the Nicaraguan problem, but he gave no details. He said he planned to discuss these ideas with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> after his return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Contra supporters in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been discussing the possibility of seeking approval for new military aid for the rebels to be placed in an escrow account. The Contras have received no military aid since Feb. 29, and congressional approval of a new package of lethal assistance without conditions is thought to have scant support among lawmakers. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 17 million humanitarian aid package in late March after the rebels and the Sandinista government agreed on an interim cease-fire. Efforts by the Sandinistas and the Contras to reach agreement on a permanent cease-fire broke down June 9 and no new talks have been scheduled. The Contras have said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> backed away from their earlier promises to enact democratic reforms. The Sandinistas have said the Contras were just using the talks as a pretext to get more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who briefed reporters after <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>' meeting with the Contras said the possibility of resuming negotiations was discussed So far, the administration has said only that it plans to seek renewed aid for the Contras, but no final decision on a package was to be made until after <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s trip. The administration, by weighing the possibility of offering <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to the <LOCATION> Sandinistas </LOCATION>, appears to believe that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> may be receptive to a proposal that would benefit it economically. Despite massive support from the Soviet bloc, the Nicaraguan economy has continued to unravel, crippled by the civil war. On several occasions during his <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> trip, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has quoted Sandinista officials as saying <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s inflation rate this year is running at 20,000 percent. Economic aid would be a sharp reversal of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policy. In addition to funding the Contras, the administration has a trade embargo against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
