<FIRST>u a AM-SuperCops Bjt   07-01 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Cops, Bjt,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Super Cops Slowing Drug Traffic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRICE'S CORNER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Along just 35 miles of interstate, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cpl </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Durnan </PERSON> confiscated $ 7 million worth of drugs, money and guns last year during otherwise routine stops for traffic violations. `` You get a sense like you're absolutely doing something good,'' said <PERSON> Durnan </PERSON>, who is n't sure how many arrests he made on <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>'s short segment of I-95 `` Nothing beats the thrill of making that arrest.'' <PERSON> Durnan </PERSON>, 35, is one of a special breed that <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gospodarek </PERSON> calls `` super cops.'' In 33 states, highway patrol officers on routine patrol are part of `` Operation Pipeline,'' using traffic stops to collar criminals and make big drug busts instead of just writing speeding tickets, he said. Nationwide, 8 -LCB- percent of the nation's cocaine seizures in 1987 were executed during traffic stops and $ 18.6 million in cash was seized, according to the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Operation Pipeline,'' which began slowly in 1983-84, has forced a nationwide rerouting of drug traffic, said <PERSON> Gospodarek </PERSON>, who coordinates the program. But it is also drawing criticism from defense lawyers and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, who contend the stops are pretenses for drug searches and therefore violate the Fourth Amendment prohibition against unlawful search and seizure. In some cases the stops are discriminatory, said <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON>. `` The real question is whether the people are stopped for absolutely legitimate reasons and subsequently an officer's suspicion is aroused and he then asks consent Or if a cop sees two Hispanic males in a Cadillac with <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> plates and sees them going 66 mph _ that's not a legitimate stop,'' said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> said the courts have not ruled definitively on the issue. `` Some courts say if the car's going 66 mph in a 65 mph zone, that's a reasonable stop,'' he said. `` Other courts say if the only person stopped is a Hispanic male driving a <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> _ that's not reasonable.'' State police and <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> officials say the key to the arrests is good police work and that they do not have a profile of the type of person to pull over. `` It's strictly a traffic officer who makes a legal traffic stop and looks beyond it,'' said <PERSON> Gospodarek </PERSON>. `` A lot of troopers making the seizures are the same guys over and over _ they're super cops.'' The officers say their success is based on awareness. `` I believe after you've made your first one, it just gets in your system. The adrenalin gets flowing,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> Officer <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Ralston </PERSON>, 34, who patrols I-75, a northward route out of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` It makes you want to get back out there and make another one.'' `` I got it bad, I'll stay out there all night,'' said another <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> officer, <PERSON> Benji </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON>. DEA estimates 15.4 pounds of cocaine an hour pass through <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> on the interstate, he said. <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON>, 27, and <PERSON> Ralston </PERSON> each seized about 400 pounds of cocaine last year. `` It's a lot of fun, you never know what you'll get into,'' <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON> said. After making a traffic stop, officers look for a number of signs. Among those listed by <PERSON> Durnan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON> and other officers were nervousness, signs of false walls or altered gas tanks, the smell of air freshener, conflicting stories from driver and passenger, or the driver of a car not listed as stolen who ca n't identify the owner. Officers then ask permission to search the car or get a search warrant, <PERSON> Gospodarek </PERSON> said. He and other officers interviewed said rarely does a driver refuse consent. <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, defense attorney <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollander </PERSON> says that's because stopped drivers are n't often asked But several officers said it's because traffickers are confident the drugs are well hidden. Drug traffickers attempt to avoid areas of high numbers of arrests, but they do n't always succeed. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Detective <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Butz </PERSON> said he and his colleagues have made `` lots of arrests where they had maps to avoid <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>.'' He said the traffickers got lazy and ignored their route instructions.
