<SECOND>AM-Drought-Insects, Bjt,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insects Attack Drought-Plagued Crops; Wildlife Also Endangered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULA FROKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Grasshoppers </ORGANIZATION> and other insects left hungry by the drought are wreaking havoc on what remains in farm fields, while young trees are depending on young people scooping buckets of water from city lakes to sustain them. The good news is a low mosquito population this summer _ but `` I'd rather have the moisture on my grass,'' says <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mosquito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>. Yellowjackets and wasps may take the place of mosquitoes and be more aggressive at picnics and near garbage cans as they search for food, said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> entomologist <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>. `` It could be that they just die from a lack of food. But it also could be that they will be driven to interact with people when they might not normally do that,'' he said. Other insects also are taking a toll. `` We've definitely seen more treatment for grasshoppers than at any time I remember,'' said <PERSON> Carlyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Holen </PERSON>, area extension agent in crop pest management in northwestern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Crookston </LOCATION> office. `` Many thousands of acres have been treated over the past month, and there still are fields that need treatment that perhaps the farmers have n't even discovered yet,'' he said. Wheat-stem maggots, normally found in 1 percent of the fields in the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, are showing up this summer in 30 percent to 40 percent of the fields, <PERSON> Holen </PERSON> said. The maggots sever wheat and barley stems. Dry weather appears to be responsible for a large drop in the number of European corn borers that feed on corn plant leaves and later bore into the stem. Record dryness coupled with near-record heat during the past few months has stressed young trees and forced wildlife to change their habits. Young trees planted in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> over the past several years to replace those ravaged by Dutch elm disease are facing the dual threat of insufficient moisture and hungry insects such as aphids and bark beetles, said <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Minneapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> this week recruited 260 inner-city young people to dip buckets into the city's lakes and pour the water on young trees nearby. The lakes, highly popular for sailing, swimming and picnicking, are down slightly. The city already maintains its 160,000 young trees planted in the past 10 years with 23 water trucks. But the concern now is to spread the word via the bucket brigade to homeowners. `` We thought that if people down at the lakes saw all the kids down there watering the trees that are starting to wilt and dry, people will catch on to the news that many of the small trees are wilting and severely stressed and that they all should be out there watering,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> special projects director <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Domholt </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, which draws all its water from the depleted <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, has instituted limited lawn sprinkling restrictions; adjacent St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> is seeking voluntary conservation. Both cities have agreed to take stronger measures if the river falls below a certain point. Duck-hunters face a shortened waterfowl season this year as the birds move to regions with more moisture in search of nesting sites, said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bremicker </PERSON>, resource manager for the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. `` The drought quickly deteriorated a lot of the good breeding wetlands,'' <PERSON> Bremicker </PERSON> said. `` The ducks then delay nesting or they do n't nest at all. They move into the northern parklands in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, where we still have a lot of water _ comparatively.'' Biologists also are concerned about other game. `` Any animal has a preferred climate, and when you move outside that preferred climate birds or mammals become stressed,'' <PERSON> Bremicker </PERSON> said.
