<FIRST>u w AM-WeaponsPlants     07-01 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Plants,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Multibillion-Dollar Cost To Clean Up, Improve Defense Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Weapons Plants-List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cleaning up environmental contamination and correcting existing problems at the nation's nuclear weapons plants could cost between $ 40 billion and $ 70 billion, according to a government report released Friday. And the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> report said the price tag could be as high as $ 110 billion in order to maintain the environmental, safety and health standards at the plants through the year 2045. The report was released by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, who had requested it as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said the report puts a price tag on the department's `` shameful neglect'' toward the health and safety of the public `` We have a choice of paying the price with money or with the health and safety of our children and grandchildren,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said. `` Those who would choose to poison our own people in order to make nuclear weapons should be asked what the weapons are supposed to protect us from.'' The department issued two sets of estimates: an `` expected'' projection representing the most likely requirements for each site; and a `` high'' projection of what could be required to meet more stringent interpretations of existing laws, regulations and policies that could reasonably be imposed on the defense plants. `` Within those bounds, the cleanup of contaminated sites and corrective actions could require between $ 40 billion and $ 70 billion in addition to an ongoing base program of $ 700 million per year,'' the department concluded. However, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said the estimate does not include the cost of high-level waste disposal, long-term monitoring, the decommissioning of abandoned nuclear reactors and modernizing the weapons complex. `` The figure of $ 110 billion is labeled a ` high' estimate by <PERSON> DOE </PERSON>, but I believe it is more likely to be a floor rather than a ceiling,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said. The department's evaluation included 18 defense plants. It said most of the remedial cleanup actions could be completed within 20 years. Environmental corrective actions could include such things as improvements in stack exhaust, construction of radioactive waste treatment facilities, upgrading drinking water supplies and other activities. The department cautioned that the cost projections do not represent proposed action by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. It said the report identifies `` needs'' and will be used to formulate long-range plans, but that a decision to adopt the actions has not been made. By far the largest single price tag for cleanup and corrective actions is for the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION>. The facility, established in 1943, recycles uranium and extracts plutonium from irradiated nuclear fuel. The department estimated that cleanup and other costs at Hanford could reach $ 48 billion and that it could take until the year 2045 to complete the job. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> has finally admitted the size and the scope of the defense waste cleanup problems at Hanford,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., adding that when estimated costs of other projects not included in the report are added, the total price tag for Hanford could reach $ 64 billion The department said a sampling of possible major environmental projects at the defense production plants includes: _ An environmental restoration program at <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alamos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, $ 1.4 billion _ Environmental restoration at the Hanford site, $ 650 million _ A buried waste program at <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, $ 500 million _ Environmental restoration at the Rocky Flats plant in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, $ 345 million _ A basin closure program at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, $ 70 million _ Groundwater and soil investigations at <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, $ 59 million _ Waste pit and silo cleanup at the Feed Materials Production Center near <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, $ 40 million _ Cleanup of polychlorinated biphenyls at the <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gaseous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diffusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; $ 38 million _ Environmental, health and safety actions at the Mound plant in <LOCATION> Miamisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, $ 30 million The agency also said major safety and health projects could include plantwide fire protection at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant, $ 200 million; an upgrade of the ventilation system at the Fernald plant, $ 55 million; and an asbestos management program at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION>, $ 52 million.
