<HEAD>New Traditionalist Bishop Says Fight Just Beginning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of a traditionalist <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> seminary in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, who was excommunicated as soon as he became a bishop, said Friday he feels `` some sorrow'' for Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and the fight has just begun. Bishop <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> also said history will prove Archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>, who consecrated four bishops Thursday in defiance of the pope, is right in opposing modernism in the church. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> excommunicated all five men after the ceremony in <LOCATION> Econe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, a Briton who converted from the <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, recalled that the early Christian theologian <PERSON> Athanasius </PERSON> was excommunicated in the 4th century but eventually made a saint. <PERSON> Athanasius </PERSON> was a champion of orthodoxy in the 4th century intrigues over what became known as the Arian heresy. `` It was proved that <PERSON> Athanasius </PERSON> was right all along,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Econe </LOCATION>, the site of <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s Swiss seminary. The schism created by the consecrations and resulting excommunications was the first major split in the church since the so-called Old Catholics broke with <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in 1870 after the doctrine of papal infallibility was proclaimed. When asked what practical consequences he expected the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> sanction to bring, <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> said: `` The fight has just started. I hope that the issues begin to clear and we will come out of this dreamland in which the devil has got vast numbers of people asleep, completely unaware there is a problem. The archbishop said today that he hopes this event will lance the abscess of modernist <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> shrugged off a statement by <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>, who predicted 80 percent of <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s followers will leave him after the excommunication. `` Poor Father <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>,'' he said. `` He lives in a different world than from the world I live in.'' He was asked whether followers might be shocked by a sentence in <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s letter to the four new bishops that mentioned `` antichrists occupying the chair of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> and the posts of authority in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.'' In response, he said Christians believe there are `` many antichrists'' doing the work of `` the Antichrist, the one who is coming at the end of the world.'' `` Any enemy of the church is an antichrist,'' he said. `` It is strong language but you have to remember what the church was 30 years ago and see it today. There is no comparison. There has been a tremendous work of destruction since the Second Vatican Council.'' His reference was to the 1962-65 council that produced reforms <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> says are spreading the `` cancer of liberalism'' in the church. <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> said he was `` not sorry that the archbishop refused to enter into any compromise with those who do not understand tradition.'' To a question about whether the traditionalists were in schism, he replied that church documents prove <PERSON> Lefbvre </PERSON> is on the `` side of the absolute truth and <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> is not. Therefore it is obviously not the archbishop who can be in schism.'' <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, 48, said he did not know of the traditionalist movement when he converted to Catholicism in 1971. When asked why he went to <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s seminary, he said: `` I was sent there by a mainstream priest who did not agree with the archbishop. He is an Irishman who said, ` If you keep on opening your big mouth there is only one place for you and that's Econe'.'' He said he planned to return on July 7 to his own seminary in <LOCATION> Ridgefield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, which he said has 38 students.
