<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Drought     07-01 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drought,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Drought `Worst in 50 Years'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A severe drought in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s northwestern grainbelt is rapidly depleting wells and irrigation dams, leaving farmers with little more to do than `` stare at the sky. Vital cropland sits idle, cattle are dying and the government is wondering how it will pay for all the food it will have to import. `` We've got 15,000 tractors and 2,000 harvesting machines doing nothing,'' said <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> los </PERSON> <PERSON> Rios </PERSON>, research chief for the <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION> in the northwestern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coastal state of <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION>. Recent rains in other important agricultural areas prevented a national catastrophe, although wheat yields are down about 15 percent and other crops are expected to be off due to late planting and low soil moisture. But farmers and cattle ranchers in the northwest are facing what some have said is the worst drought in nearly half a century. Most affected are <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> and the northwestern border state of <LOCATION> Sonora </LOCATION>. They have been dry for nearly a year. `` <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> is experiencing its worst drought in memory,'' <PERSON> Rios </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. More than 20,000 head of cattle have died in <LOCATION> Sonora </LOCATION> alone, <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, president of the state <ORGANIZATION> Cattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranchers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> newspaper El Universal. Insufficient moisture in <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION> still threatens non-irrigated fields and pastureland. Cattle losses in <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s largest state bordering <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, are into the thousands and large parts of the state bypassed the corn-planting season due to parched cropland. <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION> began importing cattle from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week. `` In other years farmers would be working intensely right now,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Shwedel </PERSON>, an agriculture economist in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>. Instead, said <PERSON> Shwedel </PERSON>, `` They're staring at the sky.'' It has rained in the northeastern border state of <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leon </LOCATION>, whose capital is <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>. But the state government in this semi-arid industrial center announced this week a plan to seed clouds so to raise dam-water levels. De los <PERSON> Rios </PERSON> said 970,000 acres of cropland have been left barren, meaning production of soybean, rice, sorghum and corn will drop by 1.1 million tons in <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> alone. `` We're talking about a loss of 15 billion pesos -LRB- $ 6.5 million -RRB- in direct salaries to workers,'' he said. Agriculture production on the northwestern desert lands depends largely on irrigation, but low water levels in the dams forced the cancellation of the spring planting season in some areas. All of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s soybeans, half the sorghum and most of the corn, beans and rice are planted during the spring cycle. De los <PERSON> Rios </PERSON> said the water supply in <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION>'s seven dams has fallen to 8 percent to 10 percent of total capacity. <LOCATION> Sonora </LOCATION>'s 17 irrigation dams are down to about 25 percent of capacity, and the supply is dropping, said <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, president of the state <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>. `` Cultivations of soybean and sesame have been restricted to almost zero in the entire <LOCATION> Yaqui </LOCATION> and Mayo valleys,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> said. The two valleys total nearly 775,000 acres. <PERSON> Shwedel </PERSON> said the federal government's inflation-fighting program will face some tough challenges because of the drought. `` We're walking on a tightrope,'' he said. Under a plan to reduce inflation that hit a record 159 percent last year, the government has pledged to reduce spending and froze wages and prices of dozens of basic consumer goods. Although many crops have been salvaged, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> still is faced with spending $ 100 million to $ 700 million more than it did last year on imported food and feed, according to <PERSON> Shwedel </PERSON>. In 1987, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> spent $ 1.3 billion, he said.
