r lives,'' he said. He also demanded more restrictions on television camera crews, contending that their presence feeds the violence, but said the restrictions should not apply to print and radio reporters. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> already puts severe limits on media access, frequently declaring sites of violence to be closed military areas. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, led by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, has said the violence must stop before peace talks can begin, but also favors trading occupied territory for peace. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> opposes territorial concessions. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, said Friday the rebellion's aim goes beyond ending the occupation to a `` confrontation over everything: our existence, our independence.'' He said domestic debates over territorial compromise weaken <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s negotiating position. A report in the <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said the Arab revolt had caused several diplomatic setbacks for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Quoting sources in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, it said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> retreated from plans to raise the level of relations, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> decided not to open an embassy in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> refused to accept a resident <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> ambassador. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official confirmed <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> had decided not to open an embassy because of the uprising, but said he did not know if that was the reason for decisions by the other countries.
