<HEAD>Democrats Want High-Tech Look, Down to Balloons and Bunting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even the balloons and bunting are supposed to have a high-tech look at this month's Democratic National Convention. `` We want the people to see this thing as an organized, unified convention _ people who've got their act together,'' <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, deputy chief executive officer for the July 18-21 event, said in an interview Friday. Bold tones of red, white and blue will be replaced by `` soft blues, soft reds and gray tones'' on the podium. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said this `` more futuristic look'' will be used around The Omni and, to some degree, will replace traditional bunting. `` It's not exactly bunting,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said of the decorations planned for the skyboxes for VIPs. But he promised plenty of color using paint, bunting and flags. Balloons in some entry areas will take the form of `` air tubes,'' thick air-filled creations `` that will be intertwined in some of the architectural structures,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. Although <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' campaign has yet to set final plans for the demonstration following his acceptance speech, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> suggested balloons wo n't simply drop from nets. `` There are a lot of different ways to use balloons these days _ balloon structures, different ways of releasing them,'' he said. Still, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> promised the celebration of the nominee will include `` lots of flags, confetti, balloons, noisemakers, lots of traditional things.'' Less dramatic moments in the convention are being planned with an eye toward projecting a calm, uncluttered image, a main goal of the podium design. In past conventions, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said, `` there were always a lot of people walking behind the speaker and everything. We just wanted to eliminate a lot of that.'' So only a handful of convention officials will have seats on the main speakers' platform, and they will not be in the line of prime camera angles. Party staffers