<HEAD>Gorbachev Proclaims Party Conference a Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on Friday proclaimed the national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference a success. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> spoke after the conference of 5,000 party members adopted resolutions in what the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency called an `` unusually stormy and long'' debate. The conference formally closed after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s address, according to <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. The Soviet Communist Party leader called for construction of a monument to the victims of dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, saying, `` I think we must agree to this, and such a monument must be constructed in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, summing up the work of the four-day conference, said `` the conference has created the necessary impetus to perestroika, deepening of perestroika and the guarantee of its irreversibility.'' Referring to his proposals to restructure the Soviet government, strengthening its legislative branch and giving the president new powers, the Soviet leader said `` the conference will continue living in the society, in the discussions in the society, but now we know how we must transform the political system.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the conference adopted a packet of six resolutions, saying the debate on bureaucracy, inter-ethnic relations, and glasnost, were particularly thorny. It did not immediately say what the resolutions said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also gave a lengthy critique of the work of former <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, who appealed to the conference earlier in the day to absolve him of blame for his criticism of the slow pace of reform. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s criticisms cost him his job and his spot on the ruling Politburo. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was chosen to run the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party organization because of his experience and energy but ultimately proved he could not handle the job. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> praised the open atmosphere of the conference. `` One of the heroes of our conference was glasnost because our conference was a result of the atmosphere of sincerity that is being reflected in our society. We also discussed its limits,'' he said. He called on the Soviet media to `` publicize the real achievements of the real heroes of perestroika,'' and proclaimed that no one has a monopoly on the truth. In an apparent reference to the time of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, he said `` the printed word was a servant of arbitrary totalitarianism.'' In contrast, he said the conference had showed how the interparty debate must be carried out.
