<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     07-01 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meeting of Opposition, Government Officials Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lower-ranking government officials and intellectuals linked to the banned trade union Solidarity met secretly this week to try to reopen dialogue stymied since the imposition of martial law in 1981. The discussions, which one participant described as `` in the nature of a first meeting,'' focused on the possibility of an `` anti-crisis pact'' in which the two sides would unite behind a program to end the country's economic crisis. `` It was certainly a success that this meeting took place,'' according to the participant, referring to the virtual absence of direct talks between the government and opposition in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the imposition of martial law in 1981. Martial law was lifted in 1983, but opposition groups including the Solidarity trade union remain officially banned. The four-hour meeting Tuesday took place with the knowledge of Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Politiburo </PERSON> member <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Czyrek </PERSON>, said a source familiar with the event. He said it might lead to meetings with participation of higher-ranking officials. The participant, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the meeting ended with a decision for a later meeting that `` would be more concrete, devoted to selected problems.'' No date was set. About 25 people were invited by <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Goliszewski </PERSON>, editor of the monthly newspaper Konfrontacja -LRB- Confrontation -RRB-, and its editorial board. The publication, linked with the official national unity organization PRON, began publishing in January and has been promoting the anti-crisis pact idea. <PERSON> Goliszewski </PERSON> confirmed he called the meeting. Other sources from the opposition and the official side, demanding anonymity, provided details to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Among those reported attending from the opposition were Solidarity advisers <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bugaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intellectuals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Aleksander </PERSON> <PERSON> Paszynski </PERSON>, head of a nationwide association of private entrepreneurs which has applied for official recognition. From the authorities were Col. <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON>, head of the government public opinion polling center <PERSON> Mariusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulczynski </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and Law of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, and a parliamentary communist party leader, <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojna </PERSON>, the sources said. The meeting was known to be controversial within the opposition, which is wary of being used. One Roman Catholic intellectual, lawyer <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, said he stayed away because, `` I thought it was n't wise to hold such a meeting at this time.'' `` There were no politicians, there was no <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>,'' said the participant, referring to Solidarity chief <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. Of the representatives from the official side, he said, `` They are important advisers, but of lower rank.'' `` The discussion was definitely a political one ... An outlining of positions or stands,'' he said. `` And I think that the next meeting will be more pragmatic or technical.'' The sources said some of the participants insisted it not be publicized. It took place on `` neutral grounds,'' a hall at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, he said. The source familiar with the meeting said it was an opportunity for the government to poll a broad spectrum of the opposition on what solutions it might accept to solve <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s problems. The nation was hit by a wave of strikes last month and there has been little public enthusiasm for government economic reform steps, including steep price increases, to save <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s debt-burdened and inefficient economy. `` Both sides expressed approval of the need for rapid changes in the economy,'' the source said. `` But the opposition stressed the opinion that the changes have to be very radical.'' The most emotional discussion was reported to focus on trade unions, with the opposition demanding legalization of Solidarity, a suggestion rejected by the officials. The opposition side said it was willing to hear other government proposals that would create `` trade union pluralism,'' the source said. The sides agreed on the desirability of independent associations, political discussion clubs and a `` coalition'' form of governing in which `` representatives of independent circles'' would enter the government and the parliament, the source said. But the officials taking part in the discussion said they had no authority to make firm offers and would have to consult with their superiors, while the opposition stressed that it was not interested in `` artificial'' actions from the government or attempts to split its ranks, said the source. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> proposed talks on an `` anti-crisis pact'' in an interview published by <PERSON> Konfrontacja </PERSON> earlier this year. Czyrek, the Politburo member, repeated the formulation in an interview published in May. However the two sides have been at odds publically over what the pact would cover and who would be the government's negotiating partner. Officials have said the government could not talk to groups paid by a foreign power, or people who want the situation in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to worsen, descriptions normally applied by the official media to Solidarity. The source said such language was absent from Tuesday's meeting.
