 A former governor's declaration of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> as a sanctuary state was vague enough to be construed as carrying the weight of law, and a journalist and minister can use it as a defense against alien smuggling charges, a judge has ruled. Then-Gov. <PERSON> Toney </PERSON> <PERSON> Anaya </PERSON> declared <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> a sanctuary in 1986, a largely symbolic action aimed at people fleeing war in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It was rescinded when Gov. <PERSON> Garrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Carruthers </PERSON> took office in January 1987. <PERSON> Demetria </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a free-lance religion writer, and the Rev. <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Remer-Thamert </PERSON>, a Lutheran minister, were indicted by a federal grand jury in December on charges of conspiring to smuggle two pregnant Salvadoran women into the country in 1986. The minister contends he tried to help the women because of his religious beliefs and because he considered them to be refugees fleeing a war-torn country. He also maintains the women were to put their babies up for adoption in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because they feared conditions in their homeland. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office has said Remer-Thamert was motivated by a so-called adoption-for-profit scheme. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> has maintained she accompanied Remer-Thamert in her role as a journalist and should never have been indicted. Prosecutors have tried to prevent the minister from using his religious beliefs as a defense. They also have tried to prevent both defendants from using the sanctuary declaration. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conway </PERSON> ruled Thursday the pair should not be prohibited from offering evidence `` which could arguably show that the defendants reasonably r