<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pilot error most likely caused the collision of two Army helicopters that killed 17 soldiers during night training at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION> last March, according to a report released Friday. `` Pilot error, to wit, a reasonable mistake in judgment is the most probable explanation for the cause of this accident,'' said the report, compiled by an investigation board of six <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> officers, all aviators. But the report concluded: `` There should be no action taken against anyone as no foundation for negligence can be established. The accident was not due to lack of diligence, nor unreasonable or unprofessional conduct.'' `` Up to the point of impact, the missions were formed just as briefed,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON>, public affairs officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> base. The report said there was no evidence of a mechanical malfunction in the two UH-60 Black Hawks involved in the March 8 crash. `` Nor can it be confirmed that there were any procedural errors on the part of either crew,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. The report, however, cited other factors, including exterior and interior design features of the UH-60 <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION> and limited pilot training with night-vision goggles. Compounding the problem, the report said, was the lack of lighting on the helicopters. The report said the number and the size of position lights on the outside of the $ 4.6 million Black Hawk are inadequate. The helicopters were made by <ORGANIZATION> Sikorsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> division of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, company spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stangrone </PERSON> said the company not seen the report. But he said: `` All aircraft have some degree of field-of-view limitation. Obviously, the ideal cockpit is a glass bubble with an unobstructed view. It's a matter of design tradeoffs that consider structural integrity, ballistic tolerance, survivability and so on. ... Design and operational tradeoffs also determine the extent and intensity of exterior aircraft lighting.'' The investigation found that the collision `` was the result of the two air crews' being unable to see each other in the final moments of flight,'' according to a statement read by <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON>. The report said one of the two helicopters may not have had its anti-collision strobe light turned on as required. `` That's the only item in question _ the strobe light,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. `` Because the accident was fatal to the crew of both aircraft, it is impossible to determine exactly what caused the two aircraft to fly into each other,'' the report said. The accident occurred when a Black Hawk returning from a solo instruction flight collided with the lead helicopter in a formation of three returning from a mission to pick up soldiers in the field. The lead helicopter, struck broadside, carried 13 soldiers. The other carried four. All 17 victims, who belonged to the 101st Airborne Division at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>, were killed. The other two helicopters landed safely. Crew members on the undamaged helicopters said there was little warning that another helicopter was approaching. The pilots were wearing night-vision goggles, which amplify very small amounts of light. `` Restrictions to vision caused by door posts and structural components of the aircraft and the limited field of view of the night-vision goggles being used by both crews hampered their ability to see,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said at the news conference. The report did specifically cite the door posts. The lights on the helicopter leading the formation could `` very easily have been obscured and blended into'' city lights, he added. Pilots wearing night goggles are supposed to scan left and right repeatedly because the goggles provide only a 40-degree field of view, <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. One of the helicopters involved in the crash was in a climbing right-hand turn with its crew members looking to the right as it turned while the crew members of the other helicopter to the left were looking straight ahead, <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. The helicopter making the right turn `` would have been slightly nose up, left wing high ... so the field of vision to the left would have been obscured,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stangrone </PERSON> said one effort being made to enhance cockpit visibility is smaller instrument panels that allow for a larger wind screen. `` This effort is paced by computer technology that will result in smaller black boxes and instrument displays,'' he said.
