<HEAD>Pay For Teachers Reaches New High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Average beginning teacher salaries pushed past $ 18,000 for the first time this past school year and average pay for the entire profession reached a record high of $ 28,085, a union survey revealed Friday. Teachers earned 17 percent more on average than all American workers in 1987 and 10 percent more than all government workers, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The public is really supporting teachers. It's the seventh straight year salaries have exceeded inflation,'' said <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, an assistant research director of the AFT, which released the survey on the eve of its biennial convention. The AFT survey of state departments of education found starting salaries for the school year that just ended were $ 18,557, up 5.4 percent from a year earlier and more than double the $ 9,085 beginners were paid in 1977. The average salary for all teachers was up 5.5 percent over 1987, and <PERSON> Jewell </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, the AFT's director of research, predicted a similar increase for the school year starting this fall. The AFT salary data shows <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> at the top of the pay scale with average salaries of $ 40,510 and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> at the bottom with $ 19,758. But the AFT also ranked the states by cost-of-living and by how teachers' pay compared to salaries of other workers. The adjustment for differences in the cost of living `` shows that <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> pay teachers the most. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> -LRB- are -RRB- on the bottom.'' Adjusted for inflation, the record $ 28,085 average salary is just $ 665 more than teachers earned in 1972. The average 1972 salary of $ 9,705 is the equivalent of $ 27,420 in today's prices. Likewise, the beginning salary of $ 6,970 in 1972 is the equivalent of $ 19,739 in today's dollars _ more than today's starting salaries <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> singled out <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and the state of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> as places that are `` setting a new standard for teacher salaries.'' The 665,000-member AFT represents nearly a half-million of the nation's 2.4 million public school teachers, primarily in big cities. The 1.9 million-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which opens its convention Monday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, has 1.5 million members. `` Connecticut reported the highest salary increase _ 15.8 percent for 1987-88,'' pushing its average pay level to $ 33,776, fifth in the nation, the AFT report said. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Fondy </PERSON>, president of both the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, said that under a new four-year contract, average salaries in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> will rise from $ 38,000 to $ 46,000 by 1991, with top-scale veterans earning $ 51,000. <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> has a contract that will push its top scale past $ 55,000, plus the possibility that lead teachers will earn nearly $ 70,000. Although teaching pays more on average than other government work and more than the average job in the private sector, the report said the average male, year-round worker earned 14 percent more in 1987 than the average teacher, who gets summers off. The average female, year-round worker made only 73 percent as much as teachers, most of whom are women. The AFT said <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> all have starting salaries in excess of $ 20,000, while only <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> start teachers off at less than $ 15,000. Although they earn more on average in real dollars than they did in 1972, today's teachers are also more experienced, with nearly 16 years in the classoom compared with less than 11 years then, the AFT said.
