<TEXT>
 A federal judge sentenced a former <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> sales manager to a six-month prison term Friday for stealing $ 2.5 million from the airline in what the defendant claimed was a plan with the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> to woo moderates in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The sentence was criticized immediately by a prosecutor as being too lenient. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON> received a three-year sentence with all but six months suspended for 21 counts of mail fraud, theft and interstate transportation of stolen securities. A further order crediting <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON> with the four months he spent in a British jail following his 1986 arrest means he will only serve two months. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> acknowledged that the sentence `` will strike some as extremely lenient.'' But the judge said the <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> government had not produced `` all knowledgeable witnesses'' who might have supported <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON>'s claim there has been `` some knowledge, some acquiesence, perhaps some complicity on the part of others.'' <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON>, 37, had contended that he was authorized by the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> royal family to spend the money, including $ 1 million to help finance an initiative with the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> to make contact with moderates in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. During the trial, <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON> testified that he met with <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> in 1986 before embarking on a trip to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> where he planned to meet with the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sensi </PERSON> was arrested in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on the f