<HEAD>Ousted Moscow Party Boss Asks to Be Cleared</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Moscow-Party Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A simmering feud in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership dominated the floor Friday and the first national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference since 1941 adjourned with a burst of candor not seen since the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s infancy. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> encouraged both sides in the long-rumored dispute over dismissed <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> to have their say. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> asked the conference to clear him of blame for an angry outburst against party conservatives last fall that cost him his job and a non-voting membership on the ruling Politburo. His most powerful opponent, Kremlin No. 2 man <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, took the floor to say <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> committed many errors and had not yet learned his lesson. More delegates also rose to criticize the wayward one-time protege of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. They accused <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> of being tactless on a trip abroad and giving interviews to foreign new agencies just to boost his own prestige. One claimed <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> drove an underling to suicide. Others defended <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> in an open debate, the highlights of which were shown on television. The broadcast did not break away even for live coverage of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech closing the conference. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said <PERSON> Yelstin </PERSON> told his 5,000 fellow delegates that his only mistake in criticizing the bureaucracy last October was in speaking too soon. Extraordinary criticism of the Communist establishment was a hallmark of the four-day meeting, including at least one call for resignations of the old guard. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, 57, is an outspoken reformer who became popular with Muscovites by demanding that stores provide more food and better consumer goods. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> brought him into the leadership, but joined in denouncing him after <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s speech to an October meeting of the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s speech to the closed meeting has not been published, but reports said he offered to resign out of frustration over his inability to control the entrenched bureaucracy in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s party organization. His comments later were branded `` politically erroneous,'' and he was fired. He rekindled the controversy during last month's U.S.-Soviet summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> by calling for <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s resignation during an interview with Western television correspondents In an account carried by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told the conference Friday: `` I think my only mistake was that I spoke too early, before the 70th anniversary of the October Revolution. `` Taking to heart what happened, I ask the conference to change the decision of the plenum of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. If you find it possible to do this, you will rehabilitate me in the eyes of the Communists.'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, widely viewed as a conservative counterweight to the reform-minded <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, took the rostrum Friday evening as one of the final conference speakers. Defending his own credentials as a supporter of perestroika, as <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s ambitious modernization program is called, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> had executed some members of his family and expelled others from the party. He helped his region become self-sufficient in food while working as a party leader in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said, whereas `` the district where you, <PERSON> Boris </PERSON>, worked for nine years now has rationing of food.'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> also denounced <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> for criticizing the old guard. He credited veteran Politburo members <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> with helping <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> gain power at a crucial meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> three years ago. Without their efforts, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said, `` others might be sitting here now'' on the dais. He said the leadership is united behind <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, and declared: `` There are neither conservatives nor reformers among the leadership.'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> has `` not drawn the necessary conclusions from his mistakes and the principled criticism of his party comrades,'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in his closing speech Friday, dealt <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> the final blow. He defended the decision to give <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> the floor, saying `` We must remove all the shrouds of secrecy,'' then reviewed events that led to his dismissal, confirming many reports that have circulated in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for months but never appeared in the official media. Taking responsiblity for the decision to promote <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> to the key <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party post, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the Politburo saw his excesses but did not act quickly enough. `` At a certain stage, we saw that something was wrong,'' he said, and it became apparent <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> `` was not up to the task'' of running <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. According to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s account, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> began losing his temper, barking orders and `` being rude,'' and attacked his own party organization. `` At first we thought he might be right,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` But when he began changing one after another of the party functionaries we became concerned and told him so. It was a time when practical problems had to be solved, but he did not act accordingly.'' He said the Politburo supported <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> until, during <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s vacation last summer, the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief wrote him asking to be relieved of his responsibilities. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he kept the letter confidential until they met when he returned from vacation. `` We decided to wait'' after the 70th anniversary celebrations the first week in November, he said, but then <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> spoke out at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting. As <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> recounted the story, he referred to a record of the secret proceeding. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> wanted to accept the resignation but he decided to wait until after the anniversary. When the celebrations were over, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> went to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party headquarters to participate in the meeting at which <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was ousted. He said at the time that <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was overly ambitious.
