<HEAD>Reagan To Nominate Stalon To Additional Time On FERC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> intends to nominate <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>, a holdover member of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, to serve additional time on the commission, the White House announced Friday. <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>, 58, filled an unexpired term when he came to the commission in 1984. That term ran out last October. The law permits him to stay on for a year as long as no successor has been sworn in. On Thursday, the president said he intends to nominate <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Moler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> staff to <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>'s seat. Friday's announcement said <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>, if confirmed, would fill the remainder of the term of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Naeve </PERSON>, who resigned in March. <PERSON> Naeve </PERSON>'s term would have expired in October 1989. <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>, who fills one of the two mandatory Democratic seats, has been an intellectual force behind many of the commission's deregulatory initiatives natural gas and wholesale electricity led by the chairman, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hesse </PERSON> Fourteen Democratic senators wrote <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> several months ago asking him to renominate <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON>. Trade publications two weeks ago carried reports that Sens. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican member, had asked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> not to renominate <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON> because he could not be confirmed <PERSON> Stalon </PERSON> said he did not know what was behind the opposition to his renomination. The announcement still does not settle the commission's membership uncertainties Ms. <PERSON> Hesse </PERSON> has not been confirmed as chairman a year after her nomination. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sousa </PERSON> has resigned effective later this month and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Trabandt </PERSON>'s term expires in October.
