<FIRST>r i AM-Excommunication     07-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Excommunication,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Excommications Rare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lefebvre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The excommunication of Archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> marks one of the few times in recent years that the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has pronounced someone removed from the body of believers. In the church's history, excommunication often had political consequences and could even result in the death penalty. Today, however, the censure is intended to cut off an individual's participation in the church's spiritual life and persuade the offender to repent. The penalty has been applied to leaders, from <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> to former Argentine President <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>, as well as rebels against church teaching, such as <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON>. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> from 1946-55 and 1973-74, was excommunicated in 1955 after launching an anti-clerical campaign. It was lifted after he repented, according to <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> sources. Excommunication was even applied to communist voters in 1949 under the militantly anti-communist Pope <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON>, an action aimed at the Italian Communist Party. In recent years, however, the church has dropped all mention of communists or their supporters being excommunicated. `` It's certainly now a purely religious punishment,'' a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> official said Friday, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` During earlier times in Christian society, it had many social and political effects, but that does n't exist any more,'' the official added. An excommunicated Catholic can not participate in worship or receive the sacraments and is refused a Christian burial. In the early days of the church, Catholics were advised to shun people who had been excommunicated. By the 15th century, the church decided that such behavior was only necessary with the most serious offenders, those known as `` vitandi,'' a Latin term meaning to be avoided. Most of those excommunicated, including <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>, are considered `` tolerati,'' to be tolerated. Among the actions that can cause excommunication are abortion, violation of the confidentiality of confession and consecration of a bishop without <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> approval. It was the latter act that resulted in <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s excommunication Thursday. During the Holy Roman Empire, from about 800 to 1806, excommunication was considered grounds for the death penalty, although it was not always carried out. Political considerations sometimes played a part in excommunications. Roman Emperor <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> was excommunicated twice, in 1227 and 1239, because his growing empire threatened the independence of the Papal States. Another major excommunication battle occurred in the 16th century over <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON>'s request for a divorce. The king tried from 1527-33 to persuade the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> to grant him an annulment. The church did not budge, and <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> subsequently declared the English church independent of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. He was promptly excommunicated by <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> VII. Perhaps the most significant excommunication was that of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON>, the founder of the 16th century Reformation and of Protestantism. In 1517 Luther complained about the church practice of selling indulgences in exchange for a reduction in the penalty for sin. He widened his criticism, attacking papal authority and calling for a greater role for individual conscience. Pope <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON> excommunicated him in 1521. In recent years, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has excommunicated government officials who have attacked the church and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priests who have refused to give up government positions.
</TEXT>
