<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMONA, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> celebrated its 30th anniversary Friday, touting its many research developments and contributions to passengers safety. `` We have some of the finest scientists in the world who live here. This is probably one of the finest research environments in the world,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, the center's director, who officiated at a small cake-cutting ceremony. The center is believed to be the largest research facility of its kind in the world. More than 2,000 people work at the 5,059-acre complex and it has an annual payroll of $ 85 million for employees and contractors. The center just outside <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> has helped develop fire-retardant seat cushions, emergency evacuation chutes that wo n't melt in a fire, floor lights to guide passengers through smoky aisles, computer programs for air traffic controllers and a new warning device to help pilots avoid mid-air collisions well before other planes are in sight. Researchers also are working on projects that include finding ways of detecting bulk explosives and plastic weapons to avoid terrorist hijackings, and using satellites to assist air controllers with overseas flights, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. The technical center is largely responsible for keeping the aviation industry in line with projected air traffic growth, he said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, proposed a broadened role for the center. `` There has to be a more direct link between our research facilities and universities and colleges. We're losing opportunities, and this is an ideal site to develop a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which would provide undergraduate and graduate training ...,'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. Such an institute, although still in the planning stage, would incorporate the expertise of specialists in the aviation industry, government and universities, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Technical center employees do much of their work in laboratories, such as a giant hangar where fires are set in a hollowed-out aircraft fuselage or the airport security lab that is surrounded by barbed wire. But research also takes place in the air with test aircraft.
