<HEAD>Largest Seizure Outside Of Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An estimated 6,000 pounds of pure cocaine, sealed in blocks of chocolate, was seized at a <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> warehouse in what may be the nation's largest drug bust outside <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, officials announced Friday. The seizure, valued at $ 480 million, is likely to drive up the price of coke in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area this summer, some officials said. Three Colombian nationals, thought to be members of a major Colombian drug cartel, were arrested in a raid of the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> Imports warehouse in <LOCATION> Hicksville </LOCATION> by 50 agents Thursday night, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON>, special agent in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs inspectors stumbled on the cocaine shipment June 24 during a routine check aboard the <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> <PERSON> Lykes </PERSON> at a port in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Baish </PERSON>, agent in charge of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The shipment was from <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and the inspection was `` a cold hit,'' he said, explaining that inspectors had no tip or advance warning of the contraband. `` This was a picture perfect case,'' <PERSON> Baish </PERSON> said. `` The hit is phenomenal for us.'' He said the agents were attracted to the shipment, 1,200 cartons marked `` industrialized cocoa powder,'' because <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> is a source country for cocaine. They sunk a drill into one of the cardboard boxes and hit a metal box hidden in the inner core of the hardened chocolate, said <PERSON> Baish </PERSON>. Agents opened the carton and found the cocaine inside the metal box, he said. They re-sealed it and kept a surveillance on the shipment with the help of electronic monitoring devices, he said. When the shipment was picked up Thursday, narcotics agents followed the trucks, said <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The trucks were intercepted before reaching the warehouse and undercover agents took the place of the drivers, according to <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON>. He said the drivers were not part of the scheme and were unaware of the contents of their cargo. The agents and the three defendants unloaded the boxes into the warehouse. A few hours later when the suspects began moving some cartons out to their cars, agents made the arrests. <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Absalon </PERSON> <PERSON> Borrero </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Anz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, were charged with importation and distribution of cocaine and conspiracy to distribute cocaine. They were ordered held without bail at their arraignment before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Chrein </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> said the suspects are believed to be members of the <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> family, of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, one of three leaders in cocaine production and importation. Each box weighed about 66 pounds. Each package of cocaine within weighed six to eight pounds and was marked with the initials of the person who had ordered it, said <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> said 779 of the 1,200 cartons contained cocaine. `` This is the largest seizure in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> outside of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON>. `` And there are only two seizures in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> that are greater.'' <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> declined to comment on whether <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> Imports was connected to the scheme. He said more arrests are expected in the case. Authorities believe that agents have been successful in plugging up ports in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> which is putting pressure on smugglers to seek other areas, such as the Northeast, as ports of entry. <PERSON> Stiffel </PERSON> estimated that the cost of cocaine around <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> will increase by $ 4,000 a kilogram because of the seizure.
