a forward looking document that offers a basis for consensus and thus to our concluding efforts,'' West German Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> told the conference. `` We must not lose any more time.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> said the proposal, which also calls for the convening of a human rights conference, `` is not only the base the 35 nations can work on, but also the balancing point'' that could lead to a final agreement. Neither <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> indicated when they thought the conference might end. Among the remaining obstacles are <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s opposition to the compromise and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and Soviet-bloc differences on whether to keep tactical nuclear weapons off the agenda, as the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> insists. A final document must receive the approval of all 35 nations. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, referring to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, said the principle of consensus `` does not imply that a state can cling to proposals for which, during the long negotiations, it has been unable to gain the support of any other participating state.'' <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> told reporters he planned to confer with Romanian delegates in search of a solution. `` I ca n't say that the Romanian attitude will block the conference,'' he said.
