<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury Friday convicted <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> of murdering two of six women he abducted and kept shackled in his basement torture chamber. The case focused on whether <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> knew right from wrong when he raped and killed women he lured to his <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> home. The defense argued he is schizophrenic and not responsible for his actions. <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON>, 44, was convicted of first-degree murder, kidnapping, rape, aggravated assault and involuntary deviate sexual intercourse. He was acquitted of one count of the latter charge. Judge <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON> <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> set Saturday morning for the start of a penalty hearing. Prosecutors have said they would seek the death penalty. Jurors, chosen in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> because of pretrial publicity here, began deliberating Wednesday afternoon, and issued their verdict at 3:30 p.m. Friday. `` Thank God it was guilty of first-degree,'' said <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>, sister of <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON>, one of the women who died in <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON>'s house and who according to testimony had been sawed apart, some of her remains fed to other captives. `` Thank God that the jury listened to the case,'' she said. `` He deserved, ` Guilty, guilty, guilty.' Now I'm hoping for the death penalty. That was a brutal way for my sister to die, tortured. Nobody deserves to die like that.'' Another victim's sister, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON>, whose sister <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> was electrocuted when <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> touched live wires to her chains while she stood in a water-filled pit, said, `` I feel good. He got what he deserved.'' `` Now I hope he gets the chair and <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> can rest in peace,'' Ms. <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> said. Defense attorney <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Peruto </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> called the verdict `` a big letdown.'' He said <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> spoke to him after the verdict but declined to reveal the conversation. `` Whatever he said, he had no emotion,'' <PERSON> Peruto </PERSON> said. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said, `` The jury did an excellent job. `` It is a difficult task for a jury to perform, that is, to sit in judgment upon one's peer. This case presented very difficult and complicated legal issues, all of which the jury pondered for quite a bit of time and came to a just decision.'' During the polling of the jury, the 44-year-old <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> stared straight ahead, showing no emotion. The sole innocent verdict came in a charge involving <PERSON> Josefina </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>, a prostitute <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> seized in November 1986. It was Ms. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> who eventually escaped and brought police to <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON>'s so-called `` House of Horrors,'' where he had imprisoned the women. <PERSON> Peruto </PERSON> had argued <PERSON> Heidnik </PERSON> was insane, a `` fruitcake'' who suffered from schizophrenia first diagnosed in 1963, for which he was discharged from the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. `` This man conducted repeated sadistic acts on six defenseless persons,'' <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> argued. `` What he did was premeditated, deliberate murder. He knew what he was doing and he knew it was wrong.''
