exhumed April 4 in a forest near <LOCATION> Renkum </LOCATION> in the eastern <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> gave the court on Friday a description of <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s final hours: `` The two of us sat in the sun for a while and drank some orange juice. He -LRB- <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> -RRB- had never suspected what was going to happen to him,'' <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>, the victim's widow, and three of their children attended the trial. In October, when <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON>'s kin demanded some sign he was alive, they received his little finger. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> told police he cut the finger off after he killed the grocery baron. At the end of the eight-hour trial, <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON>, reading from a prepared statement, said: `` Words can not compensate the loathsome crimes I have committed and the immeasurable grief I have caused to the <PERSON> Heijn </PERSON> family. `` I want to say that I am sorry. I now live in a nightmare from which I shall never awake.'' A forensic psychiatrist told the court <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> was not fully responsible for his deeds at the time of the abduction. If the court accepts that finding, it could impose a limited jail sentence followed by open-ended confinement to an institution for the criminally insane. Police arrested <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON> in a raid on his home in a small <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> suburb after a huge search. <PERSON> Elsas </PERSON>' arrest followed discovery of a 250-guilder note from the ransom payment in January by a bank employee in the Dutch capital. The note was traced back to a supermarket where the suspect did his shopping. Police recovered nearly all the ransom.
