<TEXT>
 About 220 West German environmentalists scampered over a 13-foot-high section of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall into Communist territory Friday to dodge police trying to clear them away from a disputed spot near the wall. Most of them returned to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> later in the day. Police said nine protesters were arrested, but eight were released later. Authorities issued a removal order Friday after a 5-week struggle that pitted environmentalists against city developers. The demonstrators were protesting plans to build a highway through a nearby park. When more than 900 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police moved in to chase away the squatters, the protesters were already perched on the wall. They had earlier declared they would seek `` political asylum'' in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> if West German police tried to remove them. East German border guards helped the protesters over the communist-built barrier, which splits <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> into Allied and communist sectors. Some guards backed trucks up to the eastern side of the wall to make it easier for the environmentalists to jump down and escape <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police. One smiling East German guard helped one protester by pulling his bicycle over the wall. Others greeted cheering protesters with coffee, warm sausages and cigarettes. The protesters were occupying a 10-acre piece of land which formally came under <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s control at one minute after Thursday midnight. Before then, police could not legally enter the area. The property was handed over under a deal worked out with <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> this year. The protesters began occupying the land May 26. They set up a shantytown and put up barriers to protect themselves from police. The area became the scene of freq