<HEAD>Criminal Libel Charges Against Editor Dropped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prosecutor dropped criminal libel charges against a weekly newspaper editor Friday at the request of two legislators who said the case was causing the poor, rural area too much adverse publicity. State Rep. <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and state Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McGill </PERSON>, whom editor <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> accused of unspecified corruption and stealing, delivered letters to Solicitor <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON> on Friday asking him to drop the charges. `` I see no useful purpose in furthering the prosecution of <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION> said in his letter. `` I realize that vengeance is not mine but God's,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, a Baptist minister, wrote, `` God in his own time will rectify all situations.'' <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON>, who agreed to drop the rarely used counts of criminal libel, said of <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION>: `` Even though both felt seriously harmed, they did n't want to harm -LRB- <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. ... They were distressed by the negative publicity that has made the county look bad.'' <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, the 62-year-old editor of a small weekly newspaper, The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION>, was indicted by a grand jury Monday and faced a possible sentence of a year in jail if he was convicted. He was not immediately available for comment on Friday's action, a newspaper employee said. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>, the attorney for the lawmakers, said: `` Nobody ever thought this would reach the proportions that it did. I've never in my 40 years of practice here seen anything that got such national attention. The case set off a legal battle involving First Amendment rights that caught the attention of journalists across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION>