 The burning roof of a car dealership collapsed onto firefighters Friday, killing five of them in a shower of fiery debris, authorities said. The fire, which destroyed the building and contents of <ORGANIZATION> Hackensack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, apparently started shortly after 3 p.m. in the ceiling space above the rear service section of the building, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON>. <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said the roof collapsed as the firefighters inside the building were cutting a hole in the false ceiling in order to attack flames between the ceiling and the roof. `` All of a sudden the entire 60 foot square inside ceiling fell on them,'' he said, adding that four other firefighters inside at the time escaped injury. <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said the men were spraying the space between the ceiling and the roof trying to create a `` fog'' to decrease the heat of the fire. `` They did what they were supposed to do,'' he said. Killed were Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinhogen </PERSON>, firefighters <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Krejsa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Radumski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON>, officials said. They were the city's first firefighters killed in the line of duty, <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said. The fire apparently started in the ceiling above the dealership's service area. All the dealership's employees were evacuated without injuries, a <LOCATION> Hackensack </LOCATION> police spokesman said. The fire was under control by 6:30 p.m. All of <LOCATION> Hackensack </LOCATION>'s 100 firefighters answered the alarm, as well as units from surrounding towns. Fire investigtors were picking through the debris to try and determine the cause of the fire, but <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said the roof collapse may make it impossible to find the exact cause. Witnesses said a series of explosions rocked the building shortly after the fire began.
