<HEAD>Timber Industry Approves Environment Plan for Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Conservation groups applauded a decision Friday by the international timber industry to promote environment-conscious logging in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle, the world's largest tropical rainforest The U.S.-based World Wildlife Fund said the decision _ the first of its kind by the timber industry _ could slow destruction of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rainforest, a key regulator of the world's weather. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tropical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Timber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, an association of 42 producing and consuming countries, approved a $ 4 million logging and conservation project in the remote jungle state of Acre, on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, 2,800 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. The project calls for `` integrated'' development of jungle products, such as <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> nuts and rubber, as well as timber. It also calls for loggers to consult with environmental groups, government agencies, native Indians and local workers to plan long-term development to preserve the rainforest. `` This was the big one. We hope the Acre project can serve as a model not just for the rest of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> but for all tropical forests,'' <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Markham </PERSON>, press spokesman for the World Wildlife Fund, told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> at the end of a 10-day meeting of the Timber Organization. The organization's members control 95 percent of the world's $ 5.6 billion tropical timber trade As timber trade shifts away from the shrinking forests of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the mahogany-rich <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION> is seen as the next great source of hardwood. But conservationists are worried about the effect on the climate of uncontrolled logging in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> basin, a 2 million square-mile region as large as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that covers parts of seven <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries and contains a third of the world's rainforest Already the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> forest is disappearing at the rate of some 27 million acres a year, mostly at the hands of small farmers and ranchers who cut and burn the trees, <PERSON> Markham </PERSON> said. `` The rainforest is a gaseous sink for carbon dioxide. The trees soak it up. If we cut them down, there's no way to get rid of the gas. And that contributes to the greenhouse effect,'' he said. The greenhouse effect is a gradual warming of the Earth's surface because of excessive carbon dioxide and pollutants in the atmosphere that trap the sun's heat, like a greenhouse It is thought to be a possible cause of the current drought in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The Acre project, which will get about $ 3 million from the Brazilan government and the rest from the <ORGANIZATION> Timber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, is the largest approved since the organization was founded in 1986. Smaller conservation programs, similar to the Acre project, were approved for <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>. Other proposals approved at the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> meeting were: _ Development of a `` news market service,'' to help producing countries market better _ Standardization of timber specifications among member countries, to cut waste caused by conflicting measurements _ Improvement of harvesting and processing equipment The next meeting of the organization is scheduled for November in <LOCATION> Yokohama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
