<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s decision to cut the price on its crude oil exports for the first half of July has raised prospects of a possible price war, depressing oil futures prices to their lowest levels of the year. The contract for August delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, dropped 27 cents Thursday to $ 15.16 per barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. It was the lowest level for WTI since Dec. 21, 1987, when the near-term contract also finished at $ 15.16. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the July contract for home heating oil slipped 0.64 cent to 40.88 cents a gallon. The July contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 51.94 cents, down 0.68 cent from the previous strong session, when prices soared on speculation that demand would grow as the July 4th holiday neared. Traders attributed Thursday's decline largely to profit-taking. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, a senior analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s announcement made traders even more bearish about the outlook for oil prices than they had been in recent weeks Traders have been worried about overproduction by oil nations, who have created a glut that has been depressing prices. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s senior oil ministry official, <PERSON> Hammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON>, said his country would reduce its oil export prices by up to $ 1.85 a barrel for the first half of July. <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> declined to comment further. But in a later interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, he blamed the deterioration in world oil prices on some <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries that are exceeding the production quotas agreed to by all but one of the cartel's 13 members. <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON> said the action by <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, which is not a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, could prompt some <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries to increase their production to remain competitive. `` The -LRB- oil futures -RRB- market is nervous about what <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> might do'' if other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members cheated further on their quotas, <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> did not mention any <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries by name, but said that all countries should remain committed to their quotas and `` stay away from unclear selling tactics.''
