<SECOND>PM-Foreign Tourists, Bjt,0936</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Tucson To Manhattan, Foreigners Visiting In Record Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Italians are riding the range in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. West Germans are inspecting plantations in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. And Japanese are teeing up wherever they find a nice golf course. Heading into the Independence Day weekend, tourism officials were predicting the lure of the cheaper dollar would help bring a record 30.2 million foreign visitors to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year. The expected increase is modest, up less than 2 percent from 29.7 million last year. And not all of the visitors are tourists. Many come for business, as students, or to visit friends and relatives. But the financial power of foreign visitors _ they are expected to spend a record $ 22.1 billion here this year _ is reshaping the hospitality business. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is on sale,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Toohey </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, told foreign tour operators last month in a gathering held in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> in May. Americans are learning to provide the amenities they get when they travel abroad. Multilingual signs are popping up. Some big-city hotels now have same-day delivery of Japanese newspapers. Tourism professionals also say they have to cater to the particular tastes of specific nationalities. It turns out many West Germans have a fascination with the pre-Civil War South, while Europeans of all kinds feel they have n't seen <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> without a pony ride way out <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> `` I have 82 Italians here right now,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Cote </PERSON>, the owner and camp cook of the <ORGANIZATION> Tanque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Verde </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> outside <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, said Thursday. `` Cowboys and Indians are typically American, so that's a strong image for them.'' Although for some foreigners the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not become a major travel bargain _ it is not much cheaper for Canadians than it used to be and has become more expensive for Mexicans _ shifting exchange rates have doubled the power of currencies such as the Japanese yen and West German mark since early 1985. The 11.8 million Canadians who are expected to arrive this year vastly outnumber visitors from other countries, while Mexicans are second at 6.4 million, according to projections of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. But the border nations are getting less notice lately than the free-spending Japanese, who are in third place and rising rapidly. About 2.8 million Japanese are expected this year, up 30 percent from 1987, the fastest growth rate of any major country. The growth should continue under <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Ten Million Program, which seeks to double the annual number of Japanese tourists going abroad to 10 million by 1991. <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> has been a popular Japanese tourist spot, drawing about 1.2 million Japanese visitors. Tourism officials have tried to help by putting up many signs in Japanese _ perhaps too many. `` Some of them have come to me and said, ` We're going to visit in a foreign land; we ought to be able to fend for ourselves,''' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON>, senior vice president for marketing at the <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Visitors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. `` You're damned if you do and damned if you do n't.'' A step at a time, cautious Japanese tourists have ventured from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where shopping at <ORGANIZATION> Tiffany </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and bus tours through <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> are popular. Around 1986, the Japanese began to discover <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. All <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, which began direct flights between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that year, says an expansion to daily service has been held back only by a lack of pilots and planes. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a paradise of fairways and greens to the Japanese, some of whom do most of their golfing back home on multi-tiered driving ranges because it is so hard to get a tee time on crowded courses. Japanese visitors tend to stick to well-traveled routes, while Europeans are more willing to rent a car and discover <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. But even the Europeans do n't spend a lot of vacation time in heartland states such as <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Farmers from more than 25 countries are expected to compete in the plowing match during the World Ag Expo at the Amana Colonies in September, but sightseers from abroad are fairly scarce in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Skip </PERSON> <PERSON> Strittmatter </PERSON>, marketing manager for the state <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Visitors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> capitalized on the popularity of the `` North and South'' television series about the Civil War, which was shown twice in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, by offering a free trip to the Palmetto State in a joint promotion with a German women's magazine, <PERSON> Das </PERSON> <PERSON> Neue </PERSON> <PERSON> Blatt </PERSON>. The states, locales and tourist attractions that are most successful in attracting foreign visitors are the ones who began their efforts before the dollar's big decline, said <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON> <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, for example, has representatives spread from <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>. Disney World in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is famed for its marketing to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hogate </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> restaurant expects 60 percent of its customers will come from abroad this year, the culmination of marketing efforts that <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> has pushed for seven years. The French want window seats, the Japanese like ice cream and the Germans would rather have a Budweiser than a German beer, Hogate's discovered. The homework, and the sales calls to tour operators, paid off. `` When the tidal wave started to turn in our direction, we were on the receiving end,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, the sales director. `` Our name was on the tip of their tongues.''
</TEXT>
