<FIRST>r f PM-StockLetters     07-01 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stock Letters,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post-Crash Times Tough On Many Stock Market Newsletters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New for PMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newsletter editor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> remembers better times for analyzing over-the-counter stocks. `` Last year this time, you could see it when we picked a stock,'' he said. `` It moved right away. Now, we pick a stock, it may not budge.'' Meet another group of the walking wounded from last October's stock market crash _ entrepreneurs who produce the nation's investment <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> and other small purveyors of stock-market advice are finding their readership has slipped almost as badly as the Dow Jones average over the past year. `` This will be the first year my business will not have grown,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nurock </PERSON>, publisher of the Astute Investor, based in nearby <LOCATION> Paoli </LOCATION>. `` Even given the fact that I missed calling the crash, the response to my advertising has been especially poor.'' <PERSON> Nurock </PERSON> said subscriptions to his Astute Investor have dropped by 28 percent since peaking in January 1987. Since the crash, individual investors, wary of the impact of program trading on the market and the prospect of another collapse, largely have abandoned stocks. The market for advice, good or otherwise, is off sharply. Even before October, dark clouds were gathering for the newsletters. The emergence of mutual funds as major investment vehicles reduced the need to choose individual stocks. At the same time, the five-year bull market created a proliferation of investment advice in newspapers and magazines and on television. `` Suddenly, we had all this competition,'' said <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, 36, a former newspaper reporter. `` We were like the race tracks when casino gambling came along.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON>, a widely known market pundit and editor of two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> newsletters, agreed. `` It used to be when you were right, business was good,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>. `` Now you never know. Basically, the business has n't been healthy for a couple of years now.'' Newsletter issuers range from <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to individuals armed with little more than a home computer and their hunches. Some publications have thrived in the post-crash environment. <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said the subscription base of his <ORGANIZATION> Zweig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecast </ORGANIZATION> has increased by 4,000, to 14,000, since late November. Overall revenue is running 80 percent ahead of last year, he said. A one-year subscription to <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON>'s newsletter, published every three weeks, costs $ 245. <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON>, a former finance professor and a graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, attributes his circulation surge to performance. According to a rating of investment newsletters by <ORGANIZATION> Hulbert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> <PERSON> Forecast </PERSON> was the second-best performer in the five-year period that ended March 31, posting an 18.9 percent annual return on a portfolio of selected stocks. `` We basically called the crash,'' <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said. `` On Oct. 19, we were only 8 percent invested in stocks.'' Similarly, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stack </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> InvesTech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analyst </ORGANIZATION>, a newsletter published out of <LOCATION> Whitefish </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, said he began recommending that his clients get out of the market in April 1987. By early October, he was out of the market. `` Our subscription rate is up 28 percent over the past eight months,'' said Stack, a former <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> engineer who began his newsletter six years ago. Stack noted he did not escape the year unscathed: clients who heeded his advice to abandon the market in April found themselves sitting on the sidelines during last summer's run-up. `` We were getting out while the bull market was still going strong,'' he said. `` We had a 2.5 percent cancellation rate in August, which is phenomenally high for us. It was very depressing.'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, a Philadelphian who edits the New York-based publication OTC Review Special Situations, said circulation peaked at 5,000 subscriptions in the spring of 1987. Since then, subscriptions to the monthly newsletter, priced at $ 150 annually, have dropped by half despite a relatively robust recovery by over-the-counter stocks. The owner of the newsletter, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>, asked <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> to edit it at home and contracted circulation services to an outside firm. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> said his April 1 move into a second-floor bedroom was not a response to the crash, but he acknowledged that industry cost-cutting is in vogue. `` A lot of newsletters are running close to the bone now,'' he said. `` So far, I have n't suffered any real personal damage, but there's no doubt we are in for some lean times.''
</TEXT>
