<SECOND>PM-Continental Pleas, Bjt,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Bank Officers Enter Guilty Pleas In Continental Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former officer of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and a former <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> banker will seek probation after pleading guilty to charges related to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s historic near-collapse, a lawyer says. But prosecutors plan to seek prison terms for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, who admitted misapplying bank funds, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, who admitted helping <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> with the scheme. Both entered into a plea agreement Thursday before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON>, nearly two months after a trial of the pair ended in a mistrial. `` It definitely closes the chapter on the Continental Bank-Penn Square relationship,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> after <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> accepted the defendants' guilty pleas and set sentencing for Aug. 30. Each man could get 5 years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine, but <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>'s attorney said the defendants would seek probation. `` We are looking forward to getting all this behind Mr. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> after a long, long road,'' said attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Streicker </PERSON>. Penn Square failed in 1982, and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> came close to collapse two years later after the largest run on deposits in banking history, following disclosure that it held millions in poor energy-related loans. The government kept <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s doors open with a record $ 4.5 billion bailout. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, 53, a former vice president who once headed <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s oil and gas lending operation in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, said: `` I feel we've come to an agreement that's fair to everyone <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bickford </PERSON> had no comment. His client, who once had assets valued at $ 2 million, left the courtroom in tears. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> were indicted on charges of wire fraud and misapplication of bank funds, and went to trial in March. But after seven weeks, the proceeding ended May 3 when the jury became deadlocked and <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> declared a mistrial. A new trial on eight counts each of wire fraud and three counts each of misapplication of bank funds was scheduled to begin in September. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> was accused of buying millions of dollars in poor-quality loans from <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in return for kickbacks from <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 38, former head of energy lending at <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, was accused of arranging the kickbacks in the form of $ 585,000 worth of unsecured personal loans to <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> between 1980 and 1982. The jury in the first trial cleared a third defendant, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> drilling contractor <PERSON> Jere </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturgis </PERSON>, of wire fraud charges for his alleged role in a scheme to defraud <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> was accused of manipulating <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sturgis </PERSON> in schemes to save his own failing bank. The government said <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> was caught in spiraling personal debt to finance a luxurious lifestyle and accepted kickbacks from <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> in exchange for taking risky energy loans off <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>'s hands at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s expense. The indictment cited <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>'s involvement in $ 44 million in loans made by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> to 12 Penn Square customers. It did not say how much was recovered by the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> bank. In Thursday's guilty plea, <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> admitted arranging for <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> to buy a $ 2.25 million loan made by <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> to one of its customers to cover a bad business deal of his partner, who was already millions of dollars in debt to <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
