<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Supercomputers     07-01 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Supercomputers,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Manufacturers ``Disappointed'' At Continued Lack Of Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supercomputer manufacturers said Friday they were disappointed with the Japanese government's failure to purchase U.S.-made supercomputers despite <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s commitment last year to encourage such procurements. A bilateral agreement to promote, though not guarantee, Japanese public-sector purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supercomputers went into effect last August after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> complained that the Japanese government was favoring Japanese supercomputers over their <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> counterparts. `` I think disappointed is the word'' to describe <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer makers' feeling toward Japanese government procurement of American supercomputers, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McPhee </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Supercomputers are advanced-technology computers that perform complex calculations at rapid speed and are used in such fields as science, engineering and the military. <PERSON> McPhee </PERSON> said the first three government procurements in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> since the agreement went into effect, by the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Tohoku </ORGANIZATION> and Hokkaido universities and the High Energy Physics Laboratory, went to <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION>, which along with <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> are <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s leading computer makers. `` It's curious to us as we look at the data to see that -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms -RRB- have 80-85 percent of the supercomputer market in the rest of the world, but a relatively small share of the private sector in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and until recently had no installations in the Japanese government,'' <PERSON> McPhee </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McPhee </PERSON> headed a delegation of six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supercomputer manufacturers which conducted a trade seminar and exhibition in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> this week. The delegation consisted of <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Sutherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Myrias </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` The solutions -LRB- to performance problems -RRB- that these firms bring to the market are an attractive package for Japanese users,'' <PERSON> McPhee </PERSON> said. The delegation came to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to familiarize potential Japanese clients with their technology and to study possible joint marketing of their products with Japanese partners, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>, Prime Computer's senior manager for engineering and scientific sales support. `` We're having tremendous interest with prospects for accounts,'' <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> said. `` My experience on this mission with prospects we've talked to and the excitement and interest of our subsidiary in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for the mini-supercomputer market has been very good, and we expect some major sales in the Japanese market.''
