<FIRST>u f PM-ChemicalReports 1stLd-Writethru f0015 07-01 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Reports, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Companies Confused About Toxic Release Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs on survey after 4th graf pvs, Throughout NAM;
Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of companies may still be unaware of the need to meet today's deadline for reporting release of any one of 328 different toxic chemicals into the environment last year, says an industry representative. `` There's a tremendous amount of misunderstanding out there,'' said <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON>, dealing with the issue for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. The confusion arises because many businesses have assumed the law applies only to chemical companies, and no one has been able to mount a loud enough publicity campaign, she said. `` Throughout <ORGANIZATION> NAM </ORGANIZATION> in the past month, we've had about 1,000 calls inquiring whether a business is covered by the law, and I can count on the fingers of one hand those that were n't,'' she said Thursday. A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> public relations firm chimed in today with evidence backing up her point: Interviews with representatives of 81 companies covered by the new law found only 24 had a program to answer questions at installations using the chemicals. `` Many companies in the food, transportation and instruments industries appear to be largely unprepared,'' said a statement from <ORGANIZATION> Ketchum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, part of <ORGANIZATION> Ketchum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The 1986 law requiring the reports was one response of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to the disastrous leak in <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, of methyl isocyanate in 1984 that killed almost 3,000 people. The law potentially applies to almost all manufacturers _ the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Classification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Codes </ORGANIZATION> 20 through 39 of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has certain discretion to expand it. The agency estimates that 30,000 installations probably should file five-page forms on an average of 10 different chemicals _ a total of 1.5 million pages. Not every company must report _ only those with 10 or more employees that manufacture, import or process 75,000 pounds per year of any of the chemicals, or use 10,000 pounds per year. These threshold quantities decline in future years. Companies that process a chemical make it an ingredient of a product, for an example. An example of use, on the other hand, is cleaning with a chemical. Affected companies must report all deliberate and accidental releases as well as leaks. If measurements or calculations are unavailable, `` engineering judgment'' may be used. Reports must be made to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and to state authorities. Environmentalists are counting on the accessibility of the data in computer form to generate political support for a broader and tighter program of regulation. `` I'll tell you what the public reaction is going to be: It's not going to like the fact that the environment is used as a dumping ground for all these chemicals,'' said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheiman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, whose trade group has sent emissaries from its own ranks and from members into hundreds of newspaper offices to explain what's coming, said, `` It would not be a good thing ... if people just drew conclusions from the numbers.'' The association has encouraged member companies to release forms publicly as they file them, and <PERSON> Cathcart </PERSON> said the group is telling people, `` You should talk to people you have confidence in'' if anything about the reports arouses concern. Some of the numbers are going to be huge: about 2.2 billion pounds of toluene, a common petrochemical, are released to the air nationwide each year. No one has a good idea of the total for all the covered chemicals, or the damage being done. The 328 chemicals were specified by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from lists used by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> programs. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says slightly more than half can cause cancer, at least in animals, and 44 percent are acutely toxic. Several years ago, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimated that airborne chemicals were causing 2,000 annual deaths from cancer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
