<HEAD>Submarine Yard Employees Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf with 2 grafs to update with arrests, number of
workers on day shift; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 10,000 submarine builders at the Electric Boat shipyard went on strike today after refusing to accept the company's offer of lump-sum bonuses instead of wage increases over the next three years. The Metal Trades Council, representing more than half of the shipyard's 18,000 workers, negotiated with the company until a half hour before the midnight deadline before announcing an impasse. No new talks were planned, union and company officials said early today. About 300 chanting pickets marched outside the gates of the giant yard under sunny skies this morning. City police reported two arrests, one of a man setting off fireworks and another of a man who allegedly drove his car through police barricades in front of the plant, nearly hitting some pickets. Company officials did n't know how many people stayed off the job today. Union officials said 5,000 blue-collar workers normally report for the first shift. The submarine workers voted 4,921-3 ,140 Thursday to reject the latest contract offer from <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Electric Boat is one of only two shipyards making nuclear submarines for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, and the only manufacturer of giant subs capable of carrying the Trident ballistic Electric Boat General Manager <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tovar </PERSON> said a strike will not stop submarine construction. The company made arrangements to reassign 3,000 of its 8,000 salaried employees to new jobs within the yard, he said. Electric Boat offered employees bonuses worth 5 percent of a worker's wages during the first contract year and 4 percent during the second and third years of the pact. The union demanded wage increases of 5 percent, 4 percent and 4 percent. The shipyard said it could not afford to raise base pay if it was to remain competitive in its pursuit of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts. `` We have maintained steadfastly that not increasing the base -LRB- pay -RRB- is what is going to close the competitive disadvantage we have with <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruenzel </PERSON>. Pickets went up one minute past midnight outside the shipyard's main gate, located along the <LOCATION> Thames </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that flows into eastern <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> `` No one likes to see a strike,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Messier </PERSON>. `` The company does n't like to see it, the union does n't like to see it, the community does n't like to see it, but it just comes down to you've just got to do what you've got to do.'' The last strike at the shipyard was in 1975, when the union walked out for five months and the region's economy sagged. Electric Boat's final offer, presented Monday, called for bonuses totaling $ 4,250 over three years for a first-class mechanic making $ 12.02 an hour, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sotir </PERSON>, vice president of human resources. Earlier Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> awarded this year's third and final SSN-688 attack submarine contract to Electric Boat. The $ 347.4 million contract will go to <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION>'s main shipyard here and its other plant, in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, which is unaffected by the strike. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which pays its workers 60 cents an hour less than <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION>, recently won two contracts for nuclear attack submarines after it underbid Electric Boat.
</TEXT>
