<HEAD>Grafs 1-7 new with construction spending report, early stock and
bond action, picks up 7th graf pvs, ``As long as...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Big jumps in factory and office building boosted construction spending 1.1 percent in May, offsetting declines elsewhere, the government said today in a report that suggested <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers are actively investing for the future. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that building activity rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 407.1 billion in May following a 0.2 percent dip in April. In March, construction shot up 2.8 percent. The department's report put factory construction at 22.8 percent above the same level last year, a reflection of strong growth in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s manufacturing industries because of increased demand, primarily higher exports. But the report also showed a 1 percent decline in residential construction in May, another indication that higher interest rates have hurt the housing industry by making mortgage loans unaffordable to many potential homebuyers. In other economic news early today, stocks retreated in pre-weekend profit taking after a broad gain Thursday but the bond market rose on the strength of the dollar. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's resilience came despite moves Thursday by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> to raise their interest rates, which would tend to weaken the dollar. The markets also ignored a $ 99 billion rise in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign debt for 1987, reported Tursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The increase to $ 368.2 billion underscored fears by many critics that the country is living beyond its means and is losing its worldwide political and economic might. `` As long as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has to rely on foreign financing of such magnitudes, events could at literally any moment trigger a sharp turndown in our economy,'' said <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergsten </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration contends that the leap in the nation's debt during its tenure largely reflects the investment attractions in this country, with foreigners pouring in money to buy real estate, factories and securities. The other big market news Thursday was in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s commodity pits, where soybean and grain speculators drove prices up sharply, ending a two-day decline caused by rainfall on the water-starved farm belt. The buying rush came after the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued its latest 30-day outlook late Wednesday, calling for almost no rainfall in the critical areas. Elsewhere Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in May, reflecting a sharp drop in demand for aircraft that was offset by strength in other areas. It was the largest one-month decline since a 1.4 percent drop in August, but economists were n't concerned because orders had been up sharply in March and April. They said the May decline actually could be good for the economy by giving overworked factories an opportunity to catch up with unfilled orders.
