<FIRST>r f BC-Canada-Dollar     07-01 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Canada-Dollar,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Coin Will Replace Paper Bill By Mid-1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s one-dollar coin, nicknamed the Loonie because one side depicts a swimming loon, will entirely replace the paper dollar bill within two years, the government has announced. The Loonie was introduced last year under a plan to save taxpayers 175 million Canadian dollars, or about $ 145 million, over 20 years because coins have a longer circulation life than paper bills. But public acceptance of the gold-colored, 11-sided coin has been limited and most banks and stores still provide customers with dollar bills. Many Canadians have hoarded Loonies, believing the coin will share the demise of the <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> dollar coin introduced in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1979 and overwhelmingly rejected. But the federal government, acting upon recommendations of the Royal Canadian Mint and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, says production of dollar bills will cease on June 30, 1989, and the bills will cease to be legal tender about one year later, the normal life span of a paper dollar.
