<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Environment     07-01 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Environment,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Environmental Chief Demands Polluters Be Punished</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polluters should be punished for allowing rampant industrial waste to push the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to the brink of an ecological disaster, the head of the country's new environmental protection committee said Friday. <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgun </PERSON>, chief of the committee that was created in January, told a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference that `` the grave ecological situation has emerged because of the ill-considered drive to build gigantic plants.'' <PERSON> Morgun </PERSON> said the natural fertility of soils is declining, topsoil is decreasing and forests are `` in an unsatisfactory condition.'' The air in all industrial centers is polluted `` above the hygienic standards'' and `` the quality of water in the rivers worsens nearly everywhere,'' he said. He said the Caspian and Baltic seas are polluted and called the <LOCATION> Aral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> `` a disaster zone.'' `` Behind the facts of outrages upon nature and damage done to human health are certain people in science, design institutions and builders, members of state commissions, with whose blessing facilities were put into operation which destroy nature,'' <PERSON> Morgun </PERSON> said. `` Those who are responsible for the problems should be mentioned by name and be punished according to their deserts,'' he added. <PERSON> Morgun </PERSON> addressed the 5,000 delegates at the conference a day after a steelworker from the Urals city of <PERSON> Nizhny </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagil </PERSON> criticized government leaders for their failure to tackle problems he said had reached the proportions of `` a Chernobyl-like catastrophe.'' Steelworker <PERSON> Veniamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarin </PERSON> lent force to his appeal by depicting the situation in his city, where 10,000 people demonstrated earlier this year against failure to close two 45-year-old coke-fired furnaces at the city's steel mill. One Soviet media report said 54 children were stillborn in the city last year. <PERSON> Nizhny </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagil </PERSON> has a population of 403,000. <PERSON> Yarin </PERSON> said the government should devise an emergency program for up to 60 Soviet cities he said were polluted beyond all norms. The environment has become an issue of great concern to many Soviets as <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or openness, has revealed the extent of ecological damage in candid media articles. The <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region is in particularly bad shape. The area was heavily industrialized during World War II as the Soviets moved their factories eastward, away from the invading <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said in December that another Urals industrial city, <LOCATION> Ufa </LOCATION>, was unfit for human habitation. Environmental damage is also a sensitive issue in the Baltic republics, whose delegations each mentioned the need to tackle what the Estonians term an ecological `` catastrophe'' in written platforms submitted to delegates. The Communist Party chief of <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> referred Thursday to the catastrophic drop in the level of the <LOCATION> Aral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, a vast inland sea seriously depleted by schemes to irrigate the arid republics of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. A newspaper account in 1983 said excessive tapping of the sea for irrigation had halved its depth in a decade and caused the shoreline to recede 40 miles in a few years. <PERSON> Morgun </PERSON> is head of a committee established in January to deal with the mounting environmental problems. He said measures have been outlined to improve the situation, but did not immediately give any details.
