<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest airline, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION>, was established Friday under a plan to revamp the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the state-run flag carrier that has been criticized for mismanagement and inefficiency. The government announced more than a year ago plans to bring competition into civil aviation and separate <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION>'s government functions from its business management by creating six airline companies. `` The establishment of Air <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is an important achievement for <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION> in implementing the civil aviation system reform plan,'' <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yizhou </PERSON>, director general of <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION> told a reception at <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Great Hall of the People Vice Premier <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiyun </PERSON> and representatives of major international airlines that fly to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> attended the reception. A large red-and-white banner across the stage bore the words `` Air China'' and the airline's logo, a red phoenix. Attendents were dressed in the airline's new uniforms, designed by <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>. The sophisticated two-piece wool outfits and peaked cap, all in vibrant blue, contrast sharply with the ill-fitting, blue-gray pantsuits worn by <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION> stewardesses. Air <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will be the nation's major international carrier, operating 32 overseas routes to 31 cities in 24 countries. It also will operate 44 domestic routes to 30 cities. The airline, with a fleet of 46 planes and a staff of nearly 1,000, is the third and largest to be established under <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION>'s decentralization plans <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, and the Chengdu-based <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> were formed earlier this year under the decentralization plan. <ORGANIZATION> CAAC </ORGANIZATION> now has a strictly administrative role and will no longer manage airline business. The airlines operate as enterprises responsible for their own profits and losses.
