<HEAD>Ford Offers to Settle Out of Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Late-afternoon lead planned, following news conference; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has offered settlements of less than $ 1 million to each of the families of 24 children killed in a fiery church bus crash, The <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. Citing unidentified lawyers close to the case, the newspaper also reported that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which manufactured the chassis of the bus involved in the accident, offered payments to the estates of the three adults who died and to the 40 survivors of the May 14 crash, based on the severity of their injuries. Lawyer <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Skeeters </PERSON>, a spokesman for the firm that represents many of the families, would neither confirm nor deny the report. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>, who represents the families of two of the dead children, said the settlement was being offered by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and all manufacturers responsible for producing the bus, including <ORGANIZATION> Sheller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which assembled it. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> declined to disclose the size of the offers, but described them as `` attractive financially'' to the families and also a good deal for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, Mich.-based <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, said `` delicate'' negotiations were under way but declined comment on whether a settlement had been offered. <ORGANIZATION> Sheller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman did not return phone calls. The wreck occurred as the converted school bus, owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Radcliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, was returning 67 people to the church after a day at an amusement park. Police say the accident was caused by a drunken driver traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71. But investigators have said other factors combined to increase the loss of life, including the bus' lone rear exit door and crowded conditions inside. Authorities have also pointed to the bus' gas tank, which ruptured in the crash and burst into flames, with the smoke from the resulting fire blamed for all 27 deaths. The bus was apparently one of the last manufactured in 1977 before a new federal rule required bus fuel tanks be sheathed in protective cages. Prominent mass-disaster lawyers said it would be highly unusual for such a major case to be settled even before lawsuits were filed. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Coale </PERSON>, who represents one family and has been active in several air-disaster cases, said it would be `` unconscionable'' to settle so quickly without exploring whether <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> might be liable for punitive damages.
