<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose further Friday, strengthened by pre-holiday buying and the lack of central bank intervention to dampen the momentum of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's recent advances. Gold prices rose slightly in late <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after steadying in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted gold at $ 437.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 435.10 at the same time Thursday. Money brokers said there was a widespread view in foreign-exchange markets that the dollar is heading higher for now because the key industrialized democracies will tolerate the move. But they said the advance will be slow and orderly, orchestrated through occasional dollar-selling by central banks. Traders at a major Japanese bank in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, who spoke on the condition they not be identified, said they saw some significant orders for dollars Friday from large security companies, further bolstering the dollar's value. Some expressed short-term concern about possible intervention on Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market if the dollar rises too sharply. But others disagreed. `` I do n't think there's that much fear of intervention,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chorek </PERSON>, currency analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Money </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` If there was, you'd have seen it today.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar jumped 2.30 yen to close the week at 134.50 yen, its highest level since Nov. 27 when it closed at 134.75 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 134.05 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar was worth 134.43 yen, higher than its 133.04 yen-level late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound slid to its lowest point against the dollar this year, trading as low as $ 1.69. Late in the afternoon it was quoted at $ 1.7023, the lowest level since Oct. 27, and cheaper than $ 1.7085 Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fetched $ 1.6960, cheaper than its $ 1.7115 level Thursday. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday included: 1.8203 West German marks, up from 1.8155; 1.5135 Swiss francs, up from 1.5040; 1.2202 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2131; 6.1425 French francs, up from 6.1163; and 1,352.50 Italian lire, up from 1,344.75. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday: 1.8213 West German marks, up from 1.8170; 1.5130 Swiss francs, up from 1.5060; 6.1375 French francs, up from 6.1250; 2.0530 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,352.50 Italian lire, up from 1,350.38; 1.2190 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2126. Gold prices drifted in a narrow range Friday in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but rose mildly in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after a big midweek decline. On the Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery rose $ 1.90 a troy ounce to $ 437.20. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 437.50 a troy ounce, unchanged from Thursday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> it rose, closing at $ 437.50 vs. $ 436.50 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 82 cents an ounce to close at $ 440. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market, where the metal was trading at $ 6.74 a troy ounce, compared with $ 6.66 Thursday. On the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <