<TEXT>
 Financially troubled <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, once a giant farm equipment manufacturer, on Friday filed a formal reorganization plan that would formalize the sale its principal businesses. The plan, the final step required to emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. The company, which sought protection from its creditors last year, said in a statement that the sales of major assets would raise between $ 400 million and $ 425 million, which would be distributed to creditors. <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> already arranged for the sales of its assets. Last week the company announced an agreement to sell its pump business to <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 71 million. Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bueche </PERSON> called the agreement `` the final final agreement necessary to complete our reorganization plan strategy for the sale or merger of our principal businesses as going concerns.'' In April <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> said it has agreed to sell its air quality control business for $ 245 million to <ORGANIZATION> Snyder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The company estimated that, after the payment of priority claims and secured debt, unsecured creditors will recover approximately 16 to 21 percent of their claims. The reorganized <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> would, under the plan, include an office in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Allis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and two wholly-owned operating subsidiaries. They are <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates a machinery repair facility in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> KILnGAS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has four employees in its current development phase and manages a coal gasification project at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> said that the plan was conditional, among other things, on the closing of previously announced sales of the company's air filter, pump and power generation services businesses The company's existing common stock holders would receive no cash distributions and approximately 20.6 percent of the reorganized company's common stock. `` The company's goal is to have the plan consummated by year-end 1988,'' <PERSON> Bueche </PERSON> said.
