<HEAD>Corn Futures Post Limit Gains; Oat Rally Called Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn prices soared the limit for daily trading Friday but oat futures dropped sharply in what analysts said might be a signal of the end of a record-breaking rally. Wheat and soybeans advanced strongly in other action on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. On other markets, pork futures plunged the daily trading limit while cattle futures were mixed; crude oil prices dropped below $ 15 a barrel; precious metals were slightly higher; and stock-index futures retreated. Forecasts for a warm, dry July 4 weekend in the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> underpinned gains in most grain and soybean markets. `` Corn was very strong and rumors of Russian buying were rampant,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He said the Soviets were believed to have purchased 500,000 to 1 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn and an unknown amount of Argentine corn. Most corn contracts advanced the 10-cents-a-bushel limit and the limitless contract for July delivery rose even higher. Gains in the wheat and soybean pits, while substantial, were slowed by Thursday's monthly grain stocks report from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which showed larger-than-expected stocks of corn, wheat and soybeans, <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said. But it was another story in the oat pit, where prices dropped sharply on ideas that the drought-driven rally in that market was over. <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> cited rumors of oat imports from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Other experts said the reality of yield losses had finally caught up with the futures market. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oat crop, grown primarily in the northern <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, `` is basically at maturity or close enough to maturity that very little more damage is going to be done to it now than is already known,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, grain analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Oat futures prices, which hit a record $ 3.94 a bushel Thursday, likely will slip as supply-and-demand factors replace drought-damage fears, <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said. `` I think we've seen our highs for the year,'' said independent oat trader <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Homan </PERSON>. The full extent of damage to the corn crop probably will become apparent next week as stunted plants pass through the critical pollination stage and speculation will continue to drive the soybean market for another month, he said. `` You've got reality -LRB- in the oat market -RRB-, then you're a week away from reality -LRB- for corn -RRB- and a month away from reality -LRB- for soybeans -RRB- and that's how the market traded today,'' <PERSON> Homan </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a 6-to-10-day forecast after the close calling for hot, dry weather in most major growing areas for the period July 7-11. Wheat settled 10 -LCB- cents to 15 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 4.00 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 9 -RCB- cents to 15 cents higher with July at $ 3.42 a bushel; oats were 21 cents lower to 3 cents higher with July at $ 3.32 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 17 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 9.88 -LCB- a bushel. As expected, pork futures plummeted their daily limits at the opening on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and remained locked limit-down all day in reaction to Thursday's surprising <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report showing larger-than-expected increases in both the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hog herd and the breeding intentions of hog producers. Live cattle were unchanged to .95 cent higher with August at 64.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent lower to .42 cent higher with August at 73.67 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents lower across the board with July at 44.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 2 cents lower across the board with July at 35.25 cents a pound. Crude oil prices slumped below $ 15 a barrel to their lowest levels in almost two years after fluctuating wildly on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts were divided on the reasons for the drop. Some cited technical factors while others pegged the drop to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s desire to see lower oil prices West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 18 cents to 22 cents lower with August at $ 14.94 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent to .10 cent lower with August at 41.02 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .39 cent lower to .29 cent higher with August at 48.35 cents a gallon. Precious metals futures advanced slightly in light, choppy trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold was $ 1.90 to $ 2 higher with August at $ 439.60 a troy ounce; silver was .40 cent lower to 2.5 cents higher with July at $ 6.703 a troy ounce. Stock-index futures retreated o