<SECOND>BC-Earns-CSX,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>CSX Loses $160 Million In 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reported a second-quarter loss of $ 160 million mainly because of a $ 778 million special charge that will in part cover severance payments to laid-off employees. Excluding the charge, second quarter earnings would have been $ 332 million, or $ 2.12 per share. In the year-ago quarter, the transportation, energy and technology conglomerate earned $ 114 million, or 74 cents a share. Of the special charge, $ 592 million will be used for costs related to reducing the rail labor force to about 30,000 employees. About 8,200 employees will receive payments ranging from $ 30,000 to $ 50,000, except for locomotive enginemen who are covered under an existing program that calls for payments of $ 75,000. The remaining $ 186 million of the special charge covers various costs and claims pending against <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> and certain subsidiaries. Those costs are expected to result from litigation and negotiated settlements. <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> President and Chief Operating Officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON> said the employee reduction program is part of <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>'s effort to match the number of rail employees with the operating requirements of the rail system. <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> is a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Snow said <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, since its formation in 1980, has reduced the physical base of <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> from 26,748 route miles, 3,343 locomotives and 175,281 freight cars at year-end 1981 to 21,494 route miles, 2,633 locomotives and 116,063 freight cars at year-end 1987. For the first six months of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 95 million, compared with earnings of $ 199 million, or $ 1.29 per share for the first half of 1987. Without the special charge, first half earnings would have been $ 397 million, or $ 2.52 per share.
