<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall; Construction Spending Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil prices have fallen to their lowest levels in almost two years, a development that helped cool inflation concerns and lift bond prices. The contract for August delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, plunged 22 cents per 42-gallon barrel Friday, piercing the $ 15 level to settle at $ 14.94 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Along with the fall in oil, bond prices were boosted modestly by a stronger dollar and fresh foreign demand. The yield of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s key 30-year bond, which falls when prices rise, dipped to 8.83 percent from 8.85 percent late Thursday. In other economic news, construction of offices and factories increased strongly in May, the government said Friday in a report that indicated healthy economic growth. On Wall Street, stock prices fell and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.13 points to 2,131.58, closing out the week with a net loss of 11.38 points. Overall construction spending advanced 1.1 percent in May, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The increase was led by a 7.8 percent advance in office construction and a 7.7 percent advance in factory construction. In contrast, residential construction fell 1 percent. The big jump in factory construction reflected the capital spending boom occurring as manufacturers rush to expand capacity to meet sharply higher demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports. Analysts said the rise in office construction, after a sustained period of weakness, reflected strong activity in certain sections of the country such as the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and a halt to the giant plunge in building which had occurred in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, hard hit because of troubles in the oil patch. `` Cities such as <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, are enjoying good economic growth and a fair amount of offfice construction,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peach </PERSON>, senior economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is happening while the sharp declines in other areas have at least bottomed out.''
</TEXT>
