 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> and Oldsmobile divisions Friday extended through Sept. 28 buyer incentive campaigns that were to expire on Tuesday. Many of the Chevrolet rebates will be leaner, but <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> rebates will continue unchanged except for the LeSabre, which was dropped from the program, a spokeswoman said. Chevrolet also dropped its double rebate on the Nova and Spectrum subcompacts, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> McElyea </PERSON>. As intended, the program increased the number of import owners who shopped at Chevrolet dealerships, but irritated some domestic-car owners. Chevrolet trimmed rebates by $ 100 to $ 400 on Beretta and $ 300 on <LOCATION> Corsica </LOCATION> and the Cavalier two-door model and by $ 250 on Camaro, to $ 500. Rebates increased by $ 100 to $ 500 on Cavalier four-door and wagon and $ 60 on Nova and Spectrum. <PERSON> Chevrolet </PERSON> also added the Sprint to the program, with a $ 300 rebate, <PERSON> McElyea </PERSON> said. Rebates on Chevrolet trucks remain unchanged and range from $ 300 on the S-10 pickup EL model to $ 750 on the four-wheel-drive S-10 Blazer. Buick rebates range from $ 1,000 on Electra-Park Avenue to $ 400 on Skylark. <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> also added a range of option-package discounts. Meanwhile, Oldsmobile's rebates included $ 1,000 on the Oldsmobile Ninety-Eight; $ 500 on <LOCATION> Cutlass </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ciera </LOCATION>; $ 400 on <LOCATION> Cutlass </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Calais </LOCATION>, and free air conditioning on the <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> and Supreme SL. <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> said its rebates range from $ 600 on the Fiero to $ 250 on the Sunbird.
